WEBVTT

1
00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:39.340
A face.

2
00:00:42.060 --> 00:00:43.400
A fleet.

3
00:00:45.960 --> 00:00:47.320
A war.

4
00:00:50.680 --> 00:00:52.120
A man.

5
00:00:54.940 --> 00:00:56.240
A thought.

6
00:00:59.920 --> 00:01:01.260
A trick.

7
00:01:03.600 --> 00:01:06.280
A trick to break the walls of Troy.

8
00:01:08.620 --> 00:01:10.260
And burn it!

9
00:01:10.500 --> 00:01:11.900
Scream into the ground!

10
00:02:02.770 --> 00:02:04.210
What does it mean?

11
00:02:13.480 --> 00:02:14.480
A gift.

12
00:02:17.140 --> 00:02:18.540
For Athena.

13
00:02:21.480 --> 00:02:22.780
Common Gods.

14
00:02:24.100 --> 00:02:25.280
Respect their offering.

15
00:02:29.670 --> 00:02:30.920
Save it from the waves!

16
00:02:31.500 --> 00:02:32.580
Take it to Athena's temple!

17
00:02:33.860 --> 00:02:34.860
The war is over!

18
00:02:57.230 --> 00:02:58.230
Stop!

19
00:03:02.460 --> 00:03:04.330
Not this psalm.

20
00:03:14.960 --> 00:03:17.620
I want to remind them of
whose wine they're drinking.

21
00:03:18.020 --> 00:03:19.660
I don't want to desease this psalm.

22
00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:21.000
I want to desease.

23
00:03:21.280 --> 00:03:24.020
Then why do you entertain
suitors in his house night after night?

24
00:03:24.860 --> 00:03:28.200
In this world. a man does what he chooses.

25
00:03:29.200 --> 00:03:30.200
I do what I can.

26
00:03:30.319 --> 00:03:32.240
I am a man now. Mom.

27
00:03:33.520 --> 00:03:34.520
So throw them out.

28
00:03:35.620 --> 00:03:38.640
Break Zeus's law and see what they
do to you if you give them that excuse.

29
00:03:44.680 --> 00:03:46.480
I've already lost a husband.

30
00:03:47.500 --> 00:03:48.580
I don't want to lose a son.

31
00:03:49.220 --> 00:03:50.300
My dad's coming back.

32
00:03:50.700 --> 00:03:51.700
Where is he?

33
00:03:52.320 --> 00:03:54.540
Eight years since Troy fell.

34
00:03:55.120 --> 00:03:56.760
Almost twenty since he left us.

35
00:03:57.060 --> 00:03:58.060
Where is he?

36
00:04:09.260 --> 00:04:11.880
We have to welcome him
like we welcomed all of you.

37
00:04:12.340 --> 00:04:13.420
Are you calling us beggars?

38
00:04:13.480 --> 00:04:15.760
I'm saying you've been
welcome here for three years.

39
00:04:16.480 --> 00:04:18.860
We've only enjoyed your
hospitality for so long.

40
00:04:20.620 --> 00:04:22.040
Because your mother won't choose.

41
00:04:22.859 --> 00:04:24.180
She's already married.

42
00:04:24.620 --> 00:04:25.620
Odysseus is dead.

43
00:04:26.420 --> 00:04:27.620
What do you know about my dad?

44
00:04:30.740 --> 00:04:33.080
I know he kept stringing
cattle and bad wine.

45
00:04:34.020 --> 00:04:34.657
But you had the best day of your life.

46
00:04:34.681 --> 00:04:36.201
The rest of it. the first two seasons.

47
00:04:36.380 --> 00:04:37.800
I know he never came home.

48
00:04:38.440 --> 00:04:39.440
Not yet.

49
00:04:40.775 --> 00:04:43.620
You're pining for a daddy
you didn't even know.

50
00:04:44.320 --> 00:04:46.300
Like some sniffling bastard.

51
00:04:47.160 --> 00:04:48.591
Well. since none of us can really know who

52
00:04:48.615 --> 00:04:51.481
our fathers are. don't
claim that I'm lying.

53
00:04:51.580 --> 00:04:52.580
But I did know him.

54
00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:54.000
As boys.

55
00:04:54.200 --> 00:04:55.200
We watched him hunt.

56
00:04:56.980 --> 00:04:59.580
I tried to volunteer for
his expedition to Troy.

57
00:04:59.920 --> 00:05:02.277
But he told me to stay
here and keep an eye on you.

58
00:05:02.301 --> 00:05:03.840
On me or my mother.

59
00:05:05.700 --> 00:05:07.340
You can't blame me for looking at me.

60
00:05:07.460 --> 00:05:08.840
My dad is coming home.

61
00:05:09.095 --> 00:05:11.520
And his hospitality won't
be as generous as hers.

62
00:05:12.080 --> 00:05:13.560
So he doesn't follow Zeus's law then?

63
00:05:14.180 --> 00:05:16.270
Zeus's law tells us to
treat strangers as we be

64
00:05:16.294 --> 00:05:19.081
treated because they
might be gods in disguise.

65
00:05:19.805 --> 00:05:22.280
I think if established and
tenuous that you are not a god.

66
00:05:25.124 --> 00:05:27.124
Wouldn't be much of a disguise if you did.

67
00:07:15.300 --> 00:07:16.060
No. no.

68
00:07:16.200 --> 00:07:17.200
Too fast.

69
00:07:17.945 --> 00:07:18.717
How can you know?

70
00:07:18.741 --> 00:07:21.800
You don't need eyes to
hear a hasty combination.

71
00:07:22.705 --> 00:07:24.000
Mentor push him.

72
00:07:32.180 --> 00:07:33.180
Too fast.

73
00:07:42.550 --> 00:07:44.050
He's as friendly as you.

74
00:07:45.270 --> 00:07:46.690
He only answered to your father.

75
00:07:47.349 --> 00:07:48.550
Where did he get him from?

76
00:07:49.610 --> 00:07:50.610
He met right here.

77
00:07:51.374 --> 00:07:52.374
Ah.

78
00:07:59.325 --> 00:08:01.210
I'll take him.

79
00:08:01.630 --> 00:08:02.630
For your boy?

80
00:08:02.690 --> 00:08:03.690
For a hunting dog.

81
00:08:05.840 --> 00:08:07.230
Damned if he wasn't right.

82
00:08:42.480 --> 00:08:43.480
Hold still.

83
00:08:43.785 --> 00:08:44.940
How bad a scar do you want?

84
00:08:46.960 --> 00:08:48.280
Why do you always pluck your bow?

85
00:08:48.960 --> 00:08:49.960
It's only fair.

86
00:08:50.220 --> 00:08:51.220
To warn your prey?

87
00:08:51.920 --> 00:08:52.920
To fight with honor.

88
00:08:53.025 --> 00:08:54.585
You weren't fighting. you were hunting.

89
00:08:54.815 --> 00:08:56.940
Ah. hunting's nothing
but fighting with stealth.

90
00:08:57.460 --> 00:08:58.460
Clever.

91
00:08:58.690 --> 00:09:01.050
Clever. but your cleverness
is going to get you in trouble.

92
00:09:01.555 --> 00:09:02.555
Try again.

93
00:09:03.115 --> 00:09:05.380
This time. not as fast or precise.

94
00:09:05.500 --> 00:09:07.800
You can't win with a perfect defense.

95
00:09:08.100 --> 00:09:09.100
Draw the attack.

96
00:09:10.205 --> 00:09:11.205
Hesitate.

97
00:09:11.725 --> 00:09:13.980
Open your belly to your opponent's blade.

98
00:09:14.080 --> 00:09:16.000
Their attack becomes your chance.

99
00:09:47.500 --> 00:09:48.690
You teach my father that?

100
00:09:49.025 --> 00:09:50.690
No. no. he taught me.

101
00:09:51.770 --> 00:09:54.546
He said. you're not always going to be the

102
00:09:54.570 --> 00:09:58.151
strongest or the fastest.
so be the smartest.

103
00:09:58.840 --> 00:09:59.840
What would he do. huh?

104
00:10:00.505 --> 00:10:02.905
If he came back here to find
all these suitors in his house?

105
00:10:03.110 --> 00:10:03.350
Don't.

106
00:10:03.470 --> 00:10:06.210
I can't even let myself
imagine what he'd do to them.

107
00:10:06.495 --> 00:10:07.495
There are so many.

108
00:10:08.170 --> 00:10:11.570
Cut a couple down. the
others cave bullies and cowards.

109
00:10:12.550 --> 00:10:16.010
Most of them were old enough to go to
Troy. but when they saw Agamemnon's sale.

110
00:10:19.370 --> 00:10:20.709
their fathers hid them.

111
00:10:24.670 --> 00:10:28.329
And you knew Agamemnon's war
would take many years and many lives.

112
00:10:33.455 --> 00:10:35.530
So he raised his army by lottery.

113
00:10:38.570 --> 00:10:38.970
Name?

114
00:10:39.310 --> 00:10:39.647
Draw.

115
00:10:39.671 --> 00:10:40.671
Draw.

116
00:10:40.790 --> 00:10:40.990
No.

117
00:10:41.770 --> 00:10:42.050
Name?

118
00:10:42.590 --> 00:10:42.730
Antinous.

119
00:10:43.090 --> 00:10:44.090
Draw.

120
00:10:45.730 --> 00:10:46.730
Yes.

121
00:10:46.790 --> 00:10:47.790
By lots?

122
00:10:50.285 --> 00:10:52.270
Antinous told me he volunteered.

123
00:11:02.290 --> 00:11:04.790
Your boy's trying to take Sanon's place.

124
00:11:05.570 --> 00:11:06.570
I'm not going to let him.

125
00:11:06.845 --> 00:11:08.910
He needs to stay here.
take care of his family.

126
00:11:12.039 --> 00:11:13.550
You can watch over your boy too.

127
00:11:13.670 --> 00:11:14.670
Of course.

128
00:11:18.465 --> 00:11:19.465
He's with me.

129
00:11:20.565 --> 00:11:22.530
Well. he wanted Antinous to look after me.

130
00:11:22.650 --> 00:11:23.910
No. no. no.

131
00:11:24.020 --> 00:11:26.430
But Odysseus was
sensitive to a father's shame.

132
00:11:27.010 --> 00:11:28.050
He fell for these fathers.

133
00:11:28.730 --> 00:11:31.950
You and your mother meant
more to him than promises of glory.

134
00:11:33.309 --> 00:11:34.670
So he knew it would be years.

135
00:11:36.035 --> 00:11:37.035
Did he tell my mother?

136
00:11:37.390 --> 00:11:39.010
That's a question for her.

137
00:11:39.370 --> 00:11:42.190
You may ask. is he ever coming back?

138
00:11:43.915 --> 00:11:44.990
I hardest think so.

139
00:11:45.539 --> 00:11:47.190
Never known a dog reach twenty.

140
00:11:48.725 --> 00:11:50.310
But he's long outlived his master.

141
00:12:07.844 --> 00:12:09.580
I didn't mean to stop you.

142
00:12:12.660 --> 00:12:13.660
I'm in no hurry.

143
00:12:15.224 --> 00:12:17.240
You yelled at your
grandfather's burial shroud.

144
00:12:17.630 --> 00:12:18.760
It'll be time to remarry.

145
00:12:19.420 --> 00:12:20.420
Why?

146
00:12:25.840 --> 00:12:27.720
Ithaca's been without a king too long.

147
00:12:28.480 --> 00:12:29.480
They want security.

148
00:12:30.220 --> 00:12:30.640
From what?

149
00:12:31.080 --> 00:12:32.080
The people from the sea.

150
00:12:32.840 --> 00:12:34.420
That's just traveler's tales.

151
00:12:35.540 --> 00:12:37.340
All we know of the
world is traveler's tales.

152
00:12:37.420 --> 00:12:39.020
That's how we found out Troy had fallen.

153
00:12:39.900 --> 00:12:42.740
Now they all tell stories of
attacks by people from the sea.

154
00:12:44.060 --> 00:12:45.740
And who are the people from the sea?

155
00:12:46.400 --> 00:12:49.060
No one knows. but the elders
wanted the good to be prepared.

156
00:12:49.560 --> 00:12:50.000
Prepared?

157
00:12:50.515 --> 00:12:52.820
Part of the greatest
civilization ever known.

158
00:12:54.760 --> 00:12:56.037
Look at this great house.

159
00:12:56.061 --> 00:12:58.240
Stones as old as knowledge.

160
00:12:58.975 --> 00:13:01.800
At the mercy of some
greedy. unwanted guests.

161
00:13:02.865 --> 00:13:04.140
The structure's nothing.

162
00:13:05.240 --> 00:13:07.300
Without people's respect for its meaning.

163
00:13:07.920 --> 00:13:08.920
Azusa's law.

164
00:13:09.700 --> 00:13:11.300
To treat others as you would be treated.

165
00:13:12.015 --> 00:13:14.100
And the abuse that
they destroy everything.

166
00:13:15.400 --> 00:13:17.360
So how could you think
of marrying one of them?

167
00:13:17.960 --> 00:13:22.840
Because a long time ago.
your father asked me to.

168
00:13:23.545 --> 00:13:25.060
Agamemnon is our king.

169
00:13:25.834 --> 00:13:27.620
The Trojans took his brother's wife.

170
00:13:27.720 --> 00:13:29.260
Or she ran away with them.

171
00:13:29.819 --> 00:13:33.120
Either way. the walls of Troy
are said to be impregnable.

172
00:13:34.525 --> 00:13:38.460
We'll sit outside that great city.
trying to draw them into battle.

173
00:13:40.999 --> 00:13:46.240
As years go by. Telemachus
grows. and you learn life without me.

174
00:13:46.915 --> 00:13:48.780
Menelaus will give up on Helen.

175
00:13:53.925 --> 00:13:58.630
This is Agamemnon's excuse to break
Troy's control of the trading routes.

176
00:14:01.099 --> 00:14:02.310
He won't let it pass.

177
00:14:03.370 --> 00:14:04.370
Ever.

178
00:14:11.149 --> 00:14:12.750
Well. if you refuse…

179
00:14:19.129 --> 00:14:20.129
He'll take our son.

180
00:14:22.330 --> 00:14:23.330
He would never.

181
00:14:24.149 --> 00:14:27.350
He sacrificed his own
daughter for favorable winds.

182
00:14:29.115 --> 00:14:30.910
Wow. the gods want his daughter's life.

183
00:14:31.954 --> 00:14:33.570
The power of a sacrifice.

184
00:14:35.439 --> 00:14:37.810
Is in the cost to the person making it.

185
00:14:41.525 --> 00:14:42.525
That's monstrous.

186
00:14:45.639 --> 00:14:46.639
And committed.

187
00:14:50.095 --> 00:14:51.550
I won't return soon.

188
00:14:52.650 --> 00:14:53.650
If at all.

189
00:14:58.519 --> 00:14:59.519
What if we ran?

190
00:15:01.699 --> 00:15:06.830
Took you past the ship. the brightest
crew. and headed for the horizon.

191
00:15:08.999 --> 00:15:15.070
Held hands on deck as we rode
west at dusk. chasing the escaping sun.

192
00:15:18.769 --> 00:15:20.450
There's a world beyond these walls.

193
00:15:21.990 --> 00:15:26.890
Agamemnon's vengeance
would fall on all of Ithaca.

194
00:15:33.510 --> 00:15:40.890
Promise me if I don't return by
the time Telemachus comes of age.

195
00:15:41.690 --> 00:15:45.930
Promise me you'll take another husband.

196
00:15:48.550 --> 00:15:49.830
Enough sacrifices.

197
00:15:50.230 --> 00:15:51.510
Love's not a sacrifice.

198
00:15:51.930 --> 00:15:52.930
Of course it is.

199
00:15:54.219 --> 00:15:55.586
I don't want you to make it.

200
00:15:55.610 --> 00:15:56.650
It's not up to you.

201
00:15:59.430 --> 00:16:00.430
Promise me.

202
00:16:02.430 --> 00:16:03.430
No.

203
00:16:07.129 --> 00:16:08.510
Promise me you'll come back.

204
00:16:14.429 --> 00:16:15.920
What if I can't?

205
00:16:21.719 --> 00:16:24.140
Then your memory won't
be making my decisions.

206
00:16:29.410 --> 00:16:30.410
Take my pen.

207
00:16:31.405 --> 00:16:32.730
Wear it always.

208
00:16:33.030 --> 00:16:34.530
Athena will bring you home.

209
00:16:34.735 --> 00:16:36.490
I'm not sure it suits me.

210
00:16:39.524 --> 00:16:43.330
When travelers claim to have seen
you. I'll ask where you are wearing.

211
00:16:43.810 --> 00:16:45.050
and I'll know if they're lying.

212
00:16:48.819 --> 00:16:56.151
If the people from the sea are real. right
now. Ithaca has no king or as an army.

213
00:16:56.465 --> 00:16:57.870
I could take this role.

214
00:17:00.290 --> 00:17:01.290
Come.

215
00:17:13.350 --> 00:17:14.420
String it.

216
00:17:24.430 --> 00:17:25.430
That's not fair.

217
00:17:26.430 --> 00:17:27.990
You said only he could string this bow.

218
00:17:28.385 --> 00:17:29.810
He was happy to let others try.

219
00:17:32.699 --> 00:17:34.150
He'd line up all the axes.

220
00:18:06.310 --> 00:18:08.390
No one else ever did it.

221
00:18:09.645 --> 00:18:11.929
Mom. they're bleeding us
dry. so you'll be forced to

222
00:18:11.953 --> 00:18:14.311
choose one of them before I
can claim the throne myself.

223
00:18:15.465 --> 00:18:18.250
The traveler told me
Menelaus returned years ago.

224
00:18:18.560 --> 00:18:19.390
They've all returned.

225
00:18:19.550 --> 00:18:20.550
All who survived.

226
00:18:22.520 --> 00:18:23.530
Maybe he is dead.

227
00:18:24.439 --> 00:18:26.250
And if he is. then this is my palace.

228
00:18:27.570 --> 00:18:28.570
We need to know.

229
00:18:29.015 --> 00:18:31.150
I have to go to Menelaus
to find out the truth.

230
00:18:33.250 --> 00:18:35.130
Telemachus. these suitors mean you harm.

231
00:18:35.335 --> 00:18:36.630
Oh. you think I don't know that?

232
00:18:37.710 --> 00:18:40.350
Every night they push me to
give them the excuse they need.

233
00:18:40.390 --> 00:18:43.050
I'm out there on the sea. on the road.

234
00:18:44.150 --> 00:18:45.310
They won't need an excuse.

235
00:18:45.430 --> 00:18:46.430
You just won't come back.

236
00:18:48.739 --> 00:18:50.590
You don't want me to
claim the throne myself.

237
00:18:52.809 --> 00:18:56.530
You just want to keep me in my place
so that you can stay queen of Ithaca.

238
00:18:56.629 --> 00:18:59.450
I've had enough of being
queen of Ithaca without my king.

239
00:18:59.800 --> 00:19:00.800
Without your king?

240
00:19:02.589 --> 00:19:03.589
Or a king?

241
00:19:04.949 --> 00:19:07.609
And you think you're ready
to take your father's place?

242
00:19:09.890 --> 00:19:10.890
Your child.

243
00:19:21.430 --> 00:19:23.170
Too loud. Melanthias.

244
00:19:23.600 --> 00:19:25.370
Don't wear your spurs in the palace.

245
00:19:25.630 --> 00:19:27.527
You're cowherd. not a horseman.

246
00:19:27.551 --> 00:19:30.730
And you're a pig farmer. and
who are you to talk to me like that?

247
00:19:31.450 --> 00:19:34.810
A servant our master left
in charge of his herdsman.

248
00:19:35.160 --> 00:19:38.290
The master is long
gone. you blind old fool.

249
00:19:38.550 --> 00:19:41.950
And you're about as
welcome here as that dog ass.

250
00:19:42.890 --> 00:19:43.890
Argus!

251
00:19:47.310 --> 00:19:48.310
Argus!

252
00:19:49.730 --> 00:19:50.730
Argus!

253
00:19:51.110 --> 00:19:52.110
Argus!

254
00:19:53.539 --> 00:19:55.747
Sir. he didn't do anything.

255
00:19:55.771 --> 00:19:56.790
So that stink is you?

256
00:19:58.070 --> 00:19:59.350
Leave the old dog alone.

257
00:20:00.030 --> 00:20:00.510
Which one?

258
00:20:00.750 --> 00:20:01.750
Both of us.

259
00:20:02.950 --> 00:20:03.986
What did you say to me. slave?

260
00:20:04.010 --> 00:20:05.026
You just got carried away.

261
00:20:05.050 --> 00:20:06.730
Argus is my father's hunting dog.

262
00:20:06.990 --> 00:20:07.990
His hunting dog?

263
00:20:11.950 --> 00:20:13.030
Look at that thing.

264
00:20:14.890 --> 00:20:15.890
Get it out of here.

265
00:20:15.990 --> 00:20:16.390
Don't!

266
00:20:16.550 --> 00:20:17.630
Can't you see he's in pain?

267
00:20:18.330 --> 00:20:19.330
Okay.

268
00:20:19.730 --> 00:20:21.130
Then I'll put it out of his misery.

269
00:20:21.170 --> 00:20:22.170
Leave him alone!

270
00:20:27.930 --> 00:20:29.210
Come on.

271
00:20:39.530 --> 00:20:40.690
Do you see?

272
00:20:41.930 --> 00:20:42.930
You all see?

273
00:20:44.950 --> 00:20:45.950
Here. touch me!

274
00:20:46.870 --> 00:20:48.496
I have the right.

275
00:20:51.861 --> 00:20:53.280
Please don't hurt my son.

276
00:20:56.810 --> 00:20:57.810
Easy. easy.

277
00:20:59.019 --> 00:21:00.280
Young pup lost his head.

278
00:21:00.500 --> 00:21:01.500
Show some mercy.

279
00:21:03.940 --> 00:21:05.060
Drink some more of his wine.

280
00:21:05.220 --> 00:21:06.220
I'll take care of this.

281
00:21:07.080 --> 00:21:08.720
It's my father's hunting dog.

282
00:21:10.020 --> 00:21:12.280
He's only living to see Odysseus return.

283
00:21:12.480 --> 00:21:13.040
He's fine.

284
00:21:13.300 --> 00:21:16.720
I'll put him on a dung heap out front so
he can greet his master a little sooner.

285
00:21:27.030 --> 00:21:28.730
That dog stays out there!

286
00:21:30.650 --> 00:21:33.290
Next time think twice before
you offer up your life for an animal.

287
00:21:45.320 --> 00:21:46.320
You're clear.

288
00:21:48.320 --> 00:21:48.960
Prepare supplies.

289
00:21:49.100 --> 00:21:49.900
Take them down to the ships.

290
00:21:50.100 --> 00:21:51.100
Tell no one.

291
00:21:51.280 --> 00:21:52.480
Use only people you trust.

292
00:21:52.880 --> 00:21:54.216
You've freaked your mother's heart.

293
00:21:54.240 --> 00:21:56.120
If I stay. they'll force me to fight.

294
00:21:56.660 --> 00:21:57.660
No one will back me.

295
00:21:58.000 --> 00:21:59.840
I have to find out what
happened to my father.

296
00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:03.360
Ithaca will be behind me if
they know Odysseus is dead.

297
00:22:03.620 --> 00:22:04.980
The suitors will never allow that.

298
00:22:05.160 --> 00:22:06.437
You will never make it back alive.

299
00:22:06.461 --> 00:22:09.620
Tell Mentor to meet me at
the ships just before dawn.

300
00:22:10.220 --> 00:22:12.960
What do you want me to tell your mother?

301
00:22:13.840 --> 00:22:15.740
To hold out for as long as you can.

302
00:22:19.490 --> 00:22:20.010
Ship's ready.

303
00:22:20.510 --> 00:22:21.510
Tide's right.

304
00:22:22.170 --> 00:22:24.090
Have I ever told you
that you have wise eyes?

305
00:22:24.750 --> 00:22:25.750
Athena's eyes?

306
00:22:26.130 --> 00:22:27.130
Once or twice.

307
00:22:27.410 --> 00:22:29.330
You haven't even asked
me where we're going yet.

308
00:22:29.450 --> 00:22:30.450
Where are we going?

309
00:22:30.990 --> 00:22:31.990
We'll find my dad.

310
00:22:32.690 --> 00:22:33.330
He's alive.

311
00:22:33.450 --> 00:22:35.070
I can feel it in the wind and the waves.

312
00:22:35.230 --> 00:22:36.230
He's out there somewhere.

313
00:22:37.110 --> 00:22:38.270
Wandering. injured. lost.

314
00:22:38.330 --> 00:22:39.330
I don't know.

315
00:22:39.865 --> 00:22:40.865
But he's alive.

316
00:23:12.839 --> 00:23:13.839
More dreams?

317
00:23:16.404 --> 00:23:18.851
Men drowning… inside.

318
00:23:21.300 --> 00:23:23.011
Some… dark space.

319
00:23:25.630 --> 00:23:27.050
Firelight on stone.

320
00:23:27.430 --> 00:23:28.430
I don't know.

321
00:23:30.650 --> 00:23:32.030
Don't you want to remember?

322
00:23:32.450 --> 00:23:34.890
Why can't God speak in ways we understand?

323
00:23:37.559 --> 00:23:39.370
Who doesn't understand thunder?

324
00:23:40.310 --> 00:23:41.310
The fire.

325
00:23:42.350 --> 00:23:43.370
A child's smile.

326
00:23:43.750 --> 00:23:44.750
Good harvest.

327
00:23:45.350 --> 00:23:46.830
You hide yourselves from us.

328
00:23:48.950 --> 00:23:49.950
Look.

329
00:23:50.830 --> 00:23:51.830
Who's moving that cloud?

330
00:23:53.250 --> 00:23:54.250
Massing those birds?

331
00:23:55.890 --> 00:23:56.990
Who's moving the water?

332
00:23:59.410 --> 00:24:00.590
Who were you talking to?

333
00:24:03.610 --> 00:24:05.390
Athena came to me again.

334
00:24:05.900 --> 00:24:07.150
She's telling me to remember.

335
00:24:09.344 --> 00:24:10.344
To leave.

336
00:24:11.030 --> 00:24:12.030
Why would you leave?

337
00:24:12.234 --> 00:24:13.490
We have everything we need.

338
00:24:14.610 --> 00:24:16.430
How long have I been here. Calypso?

339
00:24:20.890 --> 00:24:22.710
I have a home somewhere.

340
00:24:25.750 --> 00:24:27.871
There's someone… out there.

341
00:24:28.380 --> 00:24:29.380
How do you know?

342
00:24:30.090 --> 00:24:31.090
I don't know.

343
00:24:33.430 --> 00:24:34.430
I feel.

344
00:24:50.610 --> 00:24:52.410
What we have here could last forever.

345
00:24:52.970 --> 00:24:53.970
Forever is for God.

346
00:24:54.770 --> 00:24:55.770
For your God.

347
00:24:58.250 --> 00:25:01.750
You want to remember. but what if
remembering destroys your happiness?

348
00:25:02.555 --> 00:25:03.555
Then it wasn't real.

349
00:25:11.740 --> 00:25:12.740
No.

350
00:25:12.980 --> 00:25:13.580
No more.

351
00:25:13.680 --> 00:25:14.680
But I love it.

352
00:25:15.220 --> 00:25:16.440
Stop eating the lotus.

353
00:25:17.180 --> 00:25:18.620
Tell me what you remember.

354
00:25:20.594 --> 00:25:21.620
After Troy.

355
00:25:23.860 --> 00:25:24.860
Troy.

356
00:25:30.990 --> 00:25:31.990
We won the war.

357
00:25:33.090 --> 00:25:34.090
And then what?

358
00:26:39.700 --> 00:26:41.680
Ten years on this fucking beach.

359
00:26:46.820 --> 00:26:47.960
Let's go home.

360
00:26:49.820 --> 00:26:51.060
Remember who we leave here.

361
00:26:56.130 --> 00:26:57.290
Do we have enough provisions?

362
00:26:58.450 --> 00:26:59.730
We've taken enough from Troy.

363
00:27:01.090 --> 00:27:02.590
Another stop or two won't kill us.

364
00:27:07.830 --> 00:27:08.990
And pull!

365
00:27:11.030 --> 00:27:12.190
And pull!

366
00:27:14.310 --> 00:27:15.891
And… Stole the oars.

367
00:27:16.390 --> 00:27:17.390
Rest!

368
00:27:18.410 --> 00:27:19.590
Stole the oars!

369
00:27:25.850 --> 00:27:27.150
We'll raise the sail.

370
00:27:27.450 --> 00:27:28.530
Follow the southerly winds.

371
00:27:28.850 --> 00:27:29.850
Yes. sir.

372
00:27:30.830 --> 00:27:32.990
Agamemnon's rowing west
on the known provisions route.

373
00:27:33.270 --> 00:27:34.430
He's got more mouths to feed.

374
00:27:35.530 --> 00:27:36.647
We'll find places to land.

375
00:27:36.671 --> 00:27:38.110
Are you sure it's a risk?

376
00:27:38.510 --> 00:27:40.350
That followed Agamemnon long enough.

377
00:27:41.170 --> 00:27:43.989
With a little luck and
the right winds. we'll see

378
00:27:44.013 --> 00:27:46.730
some of the world and still
be home before Agamemnon.

379
00:28:56.230 --> 00:28:58.290
Just keep the bear on the right.

380
00:29:08.790 --> 00:29:09.270
Odysseus!

381
00:29:09.570 --> 00:29:10.570
Man!

382
00:29:13.440 --> 00:29:14.440
See?

383
00:29:15.100 --> 00:29:16.420
You lucky bastard.

384
00:29:17.520 --> 00:29:18.800
We're down to our last supplies.

385
00:29:19.320 --> 00:29:20.520
Assemble a landing party.

386
00:29:20.920 --> 00:29:21.580
Food and water.

387
00:29:21.720 --> 00:29:22.720
Enough for three weeks.

388
00:29:23.360 --> 00:29:24.700
What if they won't give it?

389
00:29:26.180 --> 00:29:27.900
How badly do you want to get home?

390
00:29:29.180 --> 00:29:30.620
Get your weapons ready!

391
00:29:31.180 --> 00:29:32.180
Bagging.

392
00:29:32.580 --> 00:29:33.580
Borrowing.

393
00:29:34.280 --> 00:29:35.280
Pondering.

394
00:29:38.760 --> 00:29:42.197
Ask him why they abandoned
their village instead of welcoming us.

395
00:29:42.221 --> 00:29:44.380
They see them as Kalasori sit down.

396
00:29:45.160 --> 00:29:46.160
Exeron!

397
00:29:46.600 --> 00:29:47.996
They're waiting for the sea people.

398
00:29:48.020 --> 00:29:49.020
They're waiting for us.

399
00:29:49.100 --> 00:29:50.720
They thought we were the sea people?

400
00:29:50.920 --> 00:29:51.920
No.

401
00:29:52.060 --> 00:29:53.060
We're Greeks.

402
00:29:53.880 --> 00:29:54.880
From Ithaca.

403
00:29:55.440 --> 00:29:56.880
Maybe you heard our victory at Troy.

404
00:29:57.820 --> 00:29:59.880
We're headed west on the southerly winds.

405
00:30:00.800 --> 00:30:01.257
We're headed west on the southerly winds.

406
00:30:01.281 --> 00:30:02.237
We're headed west on the southerly winds.

407
00:30:02.261 --> 00:30:10.100
He says if we go that way. we
won't like the things we'll find.

408
00:30:11.600 --> 00:30:18.000
After years of war. no one could
stand between my men and home.

409
00:30:19.360 --> 00:30:20.360
Not even me.

410
00:30:22.180 --> 00:30:23.180
Didn't something happen?

411
00:30:39.510 --> 00:30:41.230
Chasing the escaping sun?

412
00:30:45.570 --> 00:30:47.470
There you go.

413
00:30:50.410 --> 00:30:51.650
Lucky bastard.

414
00:31:04.005 --> 00:31:06.230
No. no. no. no.

415
00:31:06.389 --> 00:31:07.990
Sheep come in flocks.

416
00:31:09.915 --> 00:31:10.915
Let's follow.

417
00:32:31.520 --> 00:32:32.520
Someone lives here.

418
00:32:34.240 --> 00:32:35.240
Yeah. they make cheese.

419
00:32:54.040 --> 00:32:55.040
Pretty good.

420
00:32:58.649 --> 00:32:59.649
There's a lot of it.

421
00:32:59.810 --> 00:33:00.810
We should leave.

422
00:33:01.519 --> 00:33:02.940
We brought nothing to trade with.

423
00:33:03.745 --> 00:33:04.745
Zeus's law.

424
00:33:05.054 --> 00:33:07.316
I don't know if whoever lives
here has heard of Zeus's law.

425
00:33:07.340 --> 00:33:08.760
Or Zeus. for that matter.

426
00:33:08.875 --> 00:33:10.340
Everyone's heard of Zeus's law.

427
00:33:11.134 --> 00:33:12.140
Get the fire going.

428
00:33:12.460 --> 00:33:13.780
We'll welcome the owner back.

429
00:34:33.469 --> 00:34:34.469
Get away from the fire.

430
00:34:54.540 --> 00:35:02.540
I think it's asleep.

431
00:37:00.380 --> 00:37:01.380
Wait.

432
00:37:05.180 --> 00:37:06.681
The… Rock.

433
00:37:13.730 --> 00:37:14.730
We can't move the rock.

434
00:37:15.019 --> 00:37:16.019
We'd be trapped.

435
00:37:24.560 --> 00:37:25.600
Spread the word.

436
00:37:26.080 --> 00:37:27.080
In the morning.

437
00:37:27.220 --> 00:37:30.080
When it lets out its flock.
we'll rush the entrance.

438
00:37:30.980 --> 00:37:31.980
Pressed up.

439
00:37:56.790 --> 00:37:57.790
Go!

440
00:38:08.950 --> 00:38:09.950
Go!

441
00:38:13.670 --> 00:38:14.670
Can

442
00:38:17.730 --> 00:38:20.810
we jam something in the cave mouth?

443
00:38:21.470 --> 00:38:22.470
Leave a gap?

444
00:38:23.270 --> 00:38:24.270
Maybe.

445
00:38:25.030 --> 00:38:26.030
But what?

446
00:38:26.830 --> 00:38:27.830
His law.

447
00:38:31.230 --> 00:38:32.230
It'll notice.

448
00:38:34.449 --> 00:38:35.510
But grab the thin end.

449
00:38:35.834 --> 00:38:36.834
Put it in the fire.

450
00:38:37.870 --> 00:38:39.130
How much rope do we have?

451
00:38:39.990 --> 00:38:40.990
How big is the flock?

452
00:38:41.390 --> 00:38:42.390
Couple dozen. maybe.

453
00:38:45.050 --> 00:38:46.050
Not too many of us.

454
00:38:46.800 --> 00:38:49.350
When it comes back.
two of us have to get out.

455
00:38:49.400 --> 00:38:50.530
Or at least get killed.

456
00:38:55.870 --> 00:38:59.090
Run low through the flock towards
the entrance and then split wide.

457
00:38:59.189 --> 00:39:00.790
So we can only grab one of them.

458
00:39:01.170 --> 00:39:01.370
Right.

459
00:39:01.769 --> 00:39:03.150
Four of us should make the run.

460
00:39:03.930 --> 00:39:04.290
Two and two.

461
00:39:04.579 --> 00:39:05.950
Why risk more men?

462
00:39:06.194 --> 00:39:07.514
There ain't two of us last night.

463
00:39:07.790 --> 00:39:09.470
We're warming up the two before he sleeps.

464
00:40:34.500 --> 00:40:35.900
No!

465
00:40:37.820 --> 00:40:38.337
No!

466
00:40:38.361 --> 00:40:39.361
No!

467
00:40:47.000 --> 00:40:48.000
No!

468
00:40:50.780 --> 00:40:51.780
No!

469
00:40:56.920 --> 00:40:58.320
NOOOOOO!

470
00:40:59.340 --> 00:41:00.297
NOOOO!

471
00:41:00.321 --> 00:41:01.321
No!

472
00:41:33.460 --> 00:41:33.640
No!

473
00:41:34.420 --> 00:41:34.420
No!

474
00:41:34.460 --> 00:41:34.460
No!

475
00:41:34.500 --> 01:23:08.976
No!

476
00:41:34.500 --> 01:23:08.977
No!

477
00:41:34.501 --> 00:41:35.501
No!

478
00:41:35.639 --> 00:41:36.639
No!

479
00:41:38.820 --> 00:41:42.100
The sun rises for me.

480
00:41:42.640 --> 00:41:43.640
It can talk.

481
00:41:45.240 --> 00:41:46.380
Why not talk before?

482
00:41:48.360 --> 00:41:49.420
Do you talk to ants?

483
00:41:50.854 --> 00:41:52.720
Should we reason with it?

484
00:41:55.440 --> 00:41:56.700
I think we're past that.

485
00:42:53.670 --> 00:43:01.670
What are you doing?

486
00:43:10.290 --> 00:43:11.290
No!

487
00:44:00.010 --> 00:44:01.410
Go!

488
00:44:03.290 --> 00:44:04.690
Go!

489
00:44:26.350 --> 00:44:28.490
Go. go. go. go. go!

490
00:44:34.050 --> 00:44:35.050
Why

491
00:44:39.510 --> 00:44:43.490
do you

492
00:44:52.920 --> 00:44:53.960
have to fire that arrow?

493
00:44:54.580 --> 00:44:56.320
We lost good soldiers to that beast.

494
00:44:56.860 --> 00:44:59.340
Yeah. and that beast
was the son of Poseidon.

495
00:45:00.140 --> 00:45:00.260
What?

496
00:45:01.040 --> 00:45:03.260
When we put its eye out.
we heard it crying his name.

497
00:45:03.780 --> 00:45:04.880
That thing was a monster.

498
00:45:05.400 --> 00:45:06.400
I heard it too.

499
00:45:07.420 --> 00:45:08.900
So now the sea is against us?

500
00:45:09.220 --> 00:45:10.037
And the wind.

501
00:45:10.061 --> 00:45:13.780
Why are we supposed to get
home with Poseidon against us?

502
00:45:13.980 --> 00:45:16.140
We can't live by omens and sacrifices.

503
00:45:18.564 --> 00:45:20.377
Do you know how many times I've heard you

504
00:45:20.401 --> 00:45:22.560
weeping. praying to
Athena since we left Troy?

505
00:45:23.154 --> 00:45:24.486
Couldn't you have shown some mercy?

506
00:45:24.510 --> 00:45:27.000
Take this.

507
00:45:29.260 --> 00:45:30.260
Wear it.

508
00:45:30.994 --> 00:45:32.620
Remember those we couldn't bury.

509
00:45:34.360 --> 00:45:36.440
The gods helped those
who helped themselves.

510
00:45:40.400 --> 00:45:45.500
From that moment. every rough sea or
headwind told the crew we were cursed.

511
00:45:47.920 --> 00:45:49.260
But where is my crew?

512
00:45:51.660 --> 00:45:53.080
When will you let me see my men?

513
00:45:54.160 --> 00:45:55.896
If I could just talk to
them. they'd help me.

514
00:45:55.920 --> 00:45:56.920
Let me remember.

515
00:45:57.200 --> 00:45:59.420
Did I have a wife. children. maybe a son?

516
00:46:00.020 --> 00:46:01.240
How long have I been here?

517
00:46:02.960 --> 00:46:03.960
A long time.

518
00:46:04.860 --> 00:46:09.580
If I had a son. how old would he be now?

519
00:46:11.980 --> 00:46:13.480
I don't know how to speak to a king.

520
00:46:14.120 --> 00:46:15.120
You'll be fine.

521
00:46:15.500 --> 00:46:16.317
Keep your mouth shut.

522
00:46:16.341 --> 00:46:20.000
But if anyone asks.
we're traders from Crete.

523
00:46:20.024 --> 00:46:23.041
and we'll figure out
how to approach the king.

524
00:46:33.670 --> 00:46:34.127
Welcome.

525
00:46:34.151 --> 00:46:35.151
Thank you.

526
00:46:35.650 --> 00:46:37.250
You seem to be having quite… This way.

527
00:46:42.650 --> 00:46:43.790
Where are you taking us?

528
00:46:44.130 --> 00:46:46.510
The king insists on
meeting strangers himself.

529
00:47:11.980 --> 00:47:12.557
Sit.

530
00:47:12.581 --> 00:47:13.581
Not you.

531
00:47:15.660 --> 00:47:16.660
You.

532
00:47:18.480 --> 00:47:21.580
Enjoy our hospitality. our suit's demands.

533
00:47:22.740 --> 00:47:24.460
But perhaps you should
tell us who you are.

534
00:47:25.760 --> 00:47:27.200
We picked the right day to arrive.

535
00:47:27.700 --> 00:47:28.940
Feast of my daughter's wedding.

536
00:47:29.700 --> 00:47:31.900
Tomorrow she leaves to start a new life.

537
00:47:32.960 --> 00:47:34.440
You don't look like a beggar.

538
00:47:35.360 --> 00:47:36.920
Imagine you know who I am.

539
00:47:38.560 --> 00:47:45.400
I now ask the son of Atreus. brother
of Agamemnon. the husband of Helen.

540
00:47:46.580 --> 00:47:47.980
Perhaps you've heard of Helen.

541
00:47:50.360 --> 00:47:51.360
Face.

542
00:47:52.060 --> 00:47:53.660
I launched a thousand ships.

543
00:47:55.540 --> 00:47:57.500
That may be now just five hundred.

544
00:48:02.770 --> 00:48:05.470
Somebody left on the
battlefields of Troy for that face.

545
00:48:05.890 --> 00:48:07.610
For your brother's ambition.

546
00:48:08.339 --> 00:48:10.290
This one looks familiar.

547
00:48:11.490 --> 00:48:12.510
Hey. Jax.

548
00:48:14.170 --> 00:48:15.170
Chocolates.

549
00:48:15.450 --> 00:48:16.450
Killies.

550
00:48:16.709 --> 00:48:19.750
I don't miss them as much
as one particular warrior.

551
00:48:20.969 --> 00:48:22.510
He was the smartest of us all.

552
00:48:25.250 --> 00:48:27.030
Ten years we rotted on that beach.

553
00:48:40.920 --> 00:48:41.920
Deadlocked.

554
00:48:42.640 --> 00:48:44.360
Fighting amongst ourselves until one day.

555
00:48:47.480 --> 00:48:49.160
They found a way.

556
00:48:51.020 --> 00:48:52.020
Odysseus.

557
00:48:52.920 --> 00:48:54.320
Did we hear the story of the horse?

558
00:48:58.140 --> 00:48:59.500
What did you hear from the inside?

559
00:49:03.889 --> 00:49:05.300
We were in there for days.

560
00:49:06.734 --> 00:49:09.200
We squeezed inside
before the ship set sail.

561
00:49:10.920 --> 00:49:13.360
Odysseus. he knew that no one
could know that we were inside.

562
00:49:13.440 --> 00:49:15.660
Not even sending the
soldier we left behind.

563
00:49:21.020 --> 00:49:24.880
The first two tides our men
drowned right in front of us.

564
00:49:29.660 --> 00:49:33.460
They silent our piss and shit.

565
00:50:00.690 --> 00:50:03.890
A gift for Athena.

566
00:50:06.270 --> 00:50:07.530
Common gods.

567
00:50:08.750 --> 00:50:09.750
Respect their offering.

568
00:51:01.630 --> 00:51:09.630
A gift for Athena.

569
00:51:25.340 --> 00:51:27.760
A gift for Athena.

570
00:51:57.180 --> 00:51:58.860
It's enough.

571
00:52:07.550 --> 00:52:10.210
It's enough for Athena.

572
00:54:49.610 --> 00:54:53.550
He knew to wait for a moonless
night around the plains of Troy.

573
00:56:38.250 --> 00:56:39.650
Come

574
00:56:44.950 --> 00:56:46.350
on!

575
00:56:46.490 --> 00:56:47.650
Come on!

576
00:56:48.550 --> 00:56:50.550
Come on!

577
00:57:20.170 --> 00:57:21.810
I think you know the rest.

578
00:57:22.184 --> 00:57:23.730
You moved by my telling it.

579
00:57:23.824 --> 00:57:25.144
You sure you're the bard singing?

580
00:57:25.719 --> 00:57:26.719
I have.

581
00:57:29.905 --> 00:57:31.850
But they weren't there with all of you.

582
00:57:32.004 --> 00:57:34.410
With your father. Odysseus.

583
00:57:37.395 --> 00:57:38.750
You still like him?

584
00:57:39.784 --> 00:57:41.350
When did you last see him?

585
00:57:42.150 --> 00:57:43.150
Troy.

586
00:57:43.750 --> 00:57:45.590
The gods granted us a righteous victory.

587
00:57:45.910 --> 00:57:46.910
Righteous.

588
00:57:47.490 --> 00:57:51.410
The gods granted our righteous
victory but did not bless our voyages.

589
00:57:52.790 --> 00:57:54.370
Took me years to get home.

590
00:57:55.174 --> 00:57:55.810
But he didn't.

591
00:57:56.114 --> 00:57:57.850
Some did and wish they hadn't.

592
00:57:58.670 --> 00:57:59.670
Tell him.

593
00:58:00.150 --> 00:58:01.710
Tell him about your brother.

594
00:58:02.190 --> 00:58:05.590
About the fate the gods bestowed
on him after your righteous struggle.

595
00:58:06.270 --> 00:58:07.450
About his hero's welcome.

596
00:58:07.650 --> 00:58:10.890
About how Agamemnon
made it home years before us.

597
00:58:11.110 --> 00:58:14.787
Tell him how he was welcomed by
his queen. my twin sister Clytemnestra.

598
00:58:14.811 --> 00:58:15.250
No.

599
00:58:15.550 --> 00:58:15.690
No.

600
00:58:16.050 --> 00:58:16.147
No.

601
00:58:16.171 --> 00:58:17.171
Tell him how she… No!

602
00:58:17.530 --> 00:58:19.290
He does not want to hear about my brother!

603
00:58:22.374 --> 00:58:23.550
He must know of his father.

604
00:58:24.584 --> 00:58:27.170
I know nothing of Odysseus since Troy.

605
00:58:27.270 --> 00:58:28.270
Nothing?

606
00:58:29.390 --> 00:58:31.110
Not from any of your men?

607
00:58:32.350 --> 00:58:34.647
Or Agamemnon's retraders
that travel the rest of the world?

608
00:58:34.671 --> 00:58:35.610
Did you come here for summers?

609
00:58:35.670 --> 00:58:36.986
Is that what you're interested in?

610
00:58:37.010 --> 00:58:38.010
Gossip?

611
00:58:38.254 --> 00:58:39.370
Are you in the right place?

612
00:58:40.010 --> 00:58:42.350
Anyone want to spin a
story about Odysseus?

613
00:58:42.900 --> 00:58:45.550
Some say he's rich or some say poor.

614
00:58:46.805 --> 00:58:49.570
Some say he perished.
some say he's imprisoned.

615
00:58:49.750 --> 00:58:50.750
What say you?

616
00:58:50.850 --> 00:58:51.850
Imprisoned?

617
00:58:53.990 --> 00:58:57.870
What kind of prison
could hold a man like that?

618
00:58:59.479 --> 00:59:00.950
Tell me what you do. remember.

619
00:59:01.790 --> 00:59:02.790
The rest will come.

620
00:59:04.150 --> 00:59:07.450
And the men became more and more
convinced that I defended Poseidon.

621
00:59:29.140 --> 00:59:30.140
Hey!

622
00:59:31.760 --> 00:59:32.760
We.

623
00:59:53.280 --> 00:59:57.300
Were hit by storm after
storm. all pushing us off course.

624
00:59:57.660 --> 00:59:59.400
Until we were truly lost.

625
01:00:18.160 --> 01:00:19.160
Hello.

626
01:00:55.275 --> 01:00:56.275
We're here in peace.

627
01:00:59.340 --> 01:01:00.470
We just need some food.

628
01:01:06.690 --> 01:01:07.690
We need food.

629
01:01:09.655 --> 01:01:10.750
Can't you understand that?

630
01:01:10.790 --> 01:01:11.790
It's just a child.

631
01:01:14.770 --> 01:01:16.450
If that's a child. what about its parents?

632
01:01:19.119 --> 01:01:20.750
Hey. shh. it's okay.

633
01:01:21.790 --> 01:01:22.567
No. no. no. no.

634
01:01:22.591 --> 01:01:24.050
Shh!

635
01:01:26.370 --> 01:01:27.530
Go!

636
01:01:44.090 --> 01:01:44.490
Go!

637
01:01:45.070 --> 01:01:46.290
Back to the ship!

638
01:01:47.050 --> 01:01:55.050
Go. go. go!

639
01:03:58.400 --> 01:03:59.800
Go!

640
01:04:02.840 --> 01:04:04.240
Go!

641
01:04:09.180 --> 01:04:09.857
Wait!

642
01:04:09.881 --> 01:04:10.881
Checkmate!

643
01:04:12.860 --> 01:04:13.860
Wait!

644
01:04:32.210 --> 01:04:33.990
Move this bastard!

645
01:05:27.990 --> 01:05:30.510
Turn to port. follow the coast.

646
01:05:31.570 --> 01:05:32.670
What if they have ships?

647
01:05:32.870 --> 01:05:34.850
We need to get as far away as possible.

648
01:05:39.180 --> 01:05:41.560
We don't have supplies
for a blind crossing.

649
01:05:42.160 --> 01:05:43.540
We've lost our way.

650
01:05:44.140 --> 01:05:47.160
We need to find food and get our bearings.

651
01:05:50.190 --> 01:05:51.190
Turn to port.

652
01:06:17.960 --> 01:06:18.960
There!

653
01:06:19.100 --> 01:06:20.100
Smoke there!

654
01:06:21.060 --> 01:06:23.500
Go fast. we'll find the
anchorage at the beach.

655
01:06:31.170 --> 01:06:32.170
Who is that?

656
01:06:36.000 --> 01:06:37.600
Former landing party.

657
01:06:40.200 --> 01:06:41.200
Tomorrow.

658
01:06:43.660 --> 01:06:44.660
Tomorrow.

659
01:06:55.330 --> 01:06:56.710
Leave someone with the tenders.

660
01:06:57.924 --> 01:06:59.350
We think you should stay.

661
01:07:01.770 --> 01:07:02.330
We?

662
01:07:02.770 --> 01:07:03.770
All of us.

663
01:07:04.505 --> 01:07:05.505
Still alive.

664
01:07:16.380 --> 01:07:17.380
Is this a mutiny?

665
01:07:17.970 --> 01:07:18.970
That's up to you.

666
01:07:23.445 --> 01:07:24.445
Give me your boat.

667
01:07:24.805 --> 01:07:26.005
I'll make sure we eat tonight.

668
01:07:26.890 --> 01:07:27.910
No matter what you find.

669
01:09:14.940 --> 01:09:16.240
No. no. it's okay!

670
01:09:16.580 --> 01:09:17.580
It's okay!

671
01:09:22.040 --> 01:09:23.040
You're okay!

672
01:09:23.160 --> 01:09:24.040
It's all right!

673
01:09:24.120 --> 01:09:25.120
No one's gonna hurt you!

674
01:09:25.200 --> 01:09:26.500
If I do what you want.

675
01:09:26.625 --> 01:09:28.760
No one is going to hurt you.

676
01:09:32.450 --> 01:09:33.727
My name's Eurylochus.

677
01:09:33.751 --> 01:09:34.751
What's your name?

678
01:09:34.990 --> 01:09:35.370
Cersei.

679
01:09:35.970 --> 01:09:36.970
Cersei?

680
01:09:37.050 --> 01:09:37.890
We need food.

681
01:09:37.974 --> 01:09:38.974
Badly.

682
01:09:39.910 --> 01:09:40.910
I have food.

683
01:09:42.830 --> 01:09:43.910
Lots of food.

684
01:10:05.140 --> 01:10:06.389
You let me?

685
01:10:09.630 --> 01:10:11.309
Your weapons were armor.

686
01:10:13.275 --> 01:10:14.275
Put it out the back.

687
01:10:50.650 --> 01:10:51.750
Put it in.

688
01:10:56.889 --> 01:10:58.550
You like my meat?

689
01:10:59.650 --> 01:11:01.809
Why do you have so much?

690
01:11:02.770 --> 01:11:05.150
You never know when strangers will come.

691
01:11:17.460 --> 01:11:18.460
Men

692
01:11:18.929 --> 01:11:20.719
with their appetites.

693
01:11:22.700 --> 01:11:24.240
Too much is never enough.

694
01:11:33.960 --> 01:11:35.360
No!

695
01:12:17.050 --> 01:12:18.450
No!

696
01:12:41.610 --> 01:12:42.610
Eurylochus!

697
01:12:45.430 --> 01:12:46.430
Eurylochus!

698
01:13:07.630 --> 01:13:08.910
They haven't come back yet!

699
01:13:09.030 --> 01:13:09.510
None of them?

700
01:13:09.670 --> 01:13:09.870
No!

701
01:13:10.370 --> 01:13:11.370
Give me your tiger.

702
01:13:14.620 --> 01:13:15.740
Stay with the boat!

703
01:13:56.825 --> 01:13:58.480
Why don't you just come here?

704
01:14:06.810 --> 01:14:08.640
Do you come from the sea?

705
01:14:10.530 --> 01:14:11.560
Are you alone?

706
01:14:16.880 --> 01:14:19.760
My pigs have taken a liking to you.

707
01:14:20.450 --> 01:14:21.450
Are you hungry?

708
01:14:23.860 --> 01:14:27.780
Leave your weapons at the door
and enjoy the hospitality of Zeus.

709
01:14:29.520 --> 01:14:30.580
Grab a hog.

710
01:14:30.740 --> 01:14:32.220
You can slaughter it for your dinner.

711
01:14:57.330 --> 01:14:59.850
Whoever you are. you're
clearly not a farmer.

712
01:15:00.730 --> 01:15:01.730
Here.

713
01:15:04.950 --> 01:15:06.100
That stew smells good.

714
01:15:10.170 --> 01:15:11.360
That's enough for just us.

715
01:15:12.820 --> 01:15:14.440
Who says it's just us?

716
01:15:16.480 --> 01:15:17.480
Who else is here?

717
01:15:18.100 --> 01:15:19.100
Who indeed?

718
01:15:32.350 --> 01:15:36.100
You say you're all alone.
but no one comes here alone.

719
01:15:37.280 --> 01:15:38.280
No?

720
01:15:38.590 --> 01:15:40.840
You can only reach this spot by sea.

721
01:15:41.820 --> 01:15:43.580
So. where are your shipmates?

722
01:15:44.820 --> 01:15:46.160
I'm looking for them.

723
01:15:47.320 --> 01:15:48.700
Anyone happen to come this way?

724
01:15:51.740 --> 01:15:53.400
But you prepared all this food.

725
01:15:53.710 --> 01:15:54.800
You're questioning me?

726
01:15:55.340 --> 01:15:56.340
You?

727
01:15:58.050 --> 01:16:02.460
The traveler who's clearly starving. it
hasn't touched the food in front of him.

728
01:16:02.865 --> 01:16:05.900
Claims to be a sailor. yet
wears a great warrior's armor.

729
01:16:07.390 --> 01:16:12.140
And who breaks Zeus's law by bringing
a dagger into his hostess's house.

730
01:16:12.705 --> 01:16:13.720
You have sharp eyes.

731
01:16:14.495 --> 01:16:15.740
Sharpen by the gods.

732
01:16:16.750 --> 01:16:17.920
Do they grant you insights?

733
01:16:19.820 --> 01:16:20.820
Truths.

734
01:16:21.380 --> 01:16:22.380
Sometimes.

735
01:16:22.785 --> 01:16:24.700
Would they tell you
where I could find my men?

736
01:16:25.705 --> 01:16:26.705
You're a man.

737
01:16:27.040 --> 01:16:28.040
That's right.

738
01:16:28.660 --> 01:16:29.660
They would.

739
01:16:29.845 --> 01:16:30.845
Then would you tell me?

740
01:16:31.815 --> 01:16:32.815
Perhaps.

741
01:16:34.560 --> 01:16:35.980
If you give me your dagger.

742
01:16:44.560 --> 01:16:47.896
Why would I help a liar
who refuses my hospitality?

743
01:16:47.920 --> 01:16:48.920
Come on.

744
01:16:58.560 --> 01:17:00.820
I remember we were here earlier.

745
01:17:01.120 --> 01:17:02.120
Now they're not.

746
01:17:08.140 --> 01:17:09.540
They moved on?

747
01:17:10.420 --> 01:17:11.420
Yes.

748
01:17:13.760 --> 01:17:15.100
Leaving their rings.

749
01:17:24.140 --> 01:17:25.140
I wouldn't.

750
01:17:26.500 --> 01:17:26.940
Don't.

751
01:17:27.400 --> 01:17:29.080
I don't know who this crow is to you.

752
01:17:29.320 --> 01:17:32.280
If you don't put that knife down.
I will throw out of it to find her.

753
01:17:32.760 --> 01:17:33.480
Don't hurt her.

754
01:17:33.720 --> 01:17:34.720
Family.

755
01:17:36.740 --> 01:17:37.740
Mother.

756
01:17:40.180 --> 01:17:41.180
Your sister.

757
01:17:44.820 --> 01:17:47.520
You did this to her like you
turned my men into pigs.

758
01:17:47.800 --> 01:17:49.437
I didn't turn your men into anything.

759
01:17:49.461 --> 01:17:50.780
Look at them.

760
01:17:51.080 --> 01:17:52.080
This is who they are.

761
01:17:52.220 --> 01:17:53.220
Look at them.

762
01:17:53.580 --> 01:17:54.580
Base.

763
01:17:54.800 --> 01:17:55.800
Disgusting.

764
01:17:55.900 --> 01:17:58.000
The primal urges that you value in battle.

765
01:17:58.720 --> 01:18:01.200
They've raped and pillaged
across the world for you.

766
01:18:01.560 --> 01:18:03.156
And you think that's against their nature?

767
01:18:03.180 --> 01:18:05.500
You think they only did that
because you ordered them too?

768
01:18:05.740 --> 01:18:09.020
A true commander thinks his
men's savagery is actually discipline.

769
01:18:10.260 --> 01:18:11.740
If you don't seem that deluded.

770
01:18:12.440 --> 01:18:14.020
But you sent them to me here.

771
01:18:14.280 --> 01:18:15.280
On my own.

772
01:18:15.900 --> 01:18:19.380
A gang of filthy soldiers with
empty bellies and hot blood.

773
01:18:21.300 --> 01:18:24.200
You thought they'd respect me and my home?

774
01:18:25.540 --> 01:18:26.540
Look at them.

775
01:18:26.840 --> 01:18:28.040
Know your own men.

776
01:18:29.240 --> 01:18:30.340
Did they hurt you?

777
01:18:31.180 --> 01:18:32.180
They would have.

778
01:18:32.680 --> 01:18:34.420
They just want to go home.

779
01:18:37.840 --> 01:18:38.840
Let them.

780
01:19:31.044 --> 01:19:32.400
Back into your disguise.

781
01:19:38.670 --> 01:19:39.670
Odysseus.

782
01:19:40.030 --> 01:19:41.150
Back to the ship.

783
01:19:41.650 --> 01:19:43.150
Take all the food you can carry.

784
01:19:44.010 --> 01:19:45.010
Leave the meat.

785
01:19:45.425 --> 01:19:46.546
You're not gonna let her live.

786
01:19:46.570 --> 01:19:47.570
She's a witch.

787
01:19:48.055 --> 01:19:49.055
Who gave her powers?

788
01:19:49.730 --> 01:19:50.730
Your gods.

789
01:19:51.100 --> 01:19:52.620
Fill the jugs and skins of the stream.

790
01:19:52.915 --> 01:19:54.030
Be ready to sail at dawn.

791
01:20:00.295 --> 01:20:01.430
Why leave her like this?

792
01:20:02.330 --> 01:20:03.610
We get on better this way.

793
01:20:05.390 --> 01:20:07.030
I'm sorry if we offended you.

794
01:20:08.650 --> 01:20:10.170
We can't get back without your help.

795
01:20:11.090 --> 01:20:12.467
We need to know the
way to the trade routes.

796
01:20:12.491 --> 01:20:13.910
You're too lost.

797
01:20:14.750 --> 01:20:15.750
What do you mean?

798
01:20:17.090 --> 01:20:19.910
Only blind Tiresias can
tell you how to go home.

799
01:20:20.570 --> 01:20:20.790
Tiresias?

800
01:20:21.119 --> 01:20:22.119
In Hades.

801
01:20:22.990 --> 01:20:25.830
Nobody sails into hell. then comes back.

802
01:20:26.235 --> 01:20:27.235
You will.

803
01:20:28.350 --> 01:20:30.530
Head north into the twilight.

804
01:20:36.230 --> 01:20:40.870
And head inland until a
river of fire meets a river of ice.

805
01:21:31.620 --> 01:21:33.320
There you must dig a trench.

806
01:21:35.575 --> 01:21:38.300
And fill it with the blood of sacrifice.

807
01:21:58.530 --> 01:21:59.630
Gather the dead.

808
01:22:01.220 --> 01:22:02.890
And learn how you go home.

809
01:22:05.070 --> 01:22:06.070
You.

810
01:22:07.100 --> 01:22:08.310
Not your men.

811
01:22:09.445 --> 01:22:10.445
You'd curse them?

812
01:22:11.110 --> 01:22:12.110
Not a curse.

813
01:22:13.155 --> 01:22:14.155
A truth.

814
01:22:15.730 --> 01:22:17.950
Your men don't want you to defy the gods.

815
01:22:20.055 --> 01:22:22.150
The gods say only you make it home.

816
01:22:23.510 --> 01:22:24.690
Then I defy the gods.

817
01:23:06.890 --> 01:23:07.890
Sinan.

818
01:23:08.170 --> 01:23:09.170
It's Odysseus.

819
01:23:14.440 --> 01:23:15.440
Sinan.

820
01:23:16.340 --> 01:23:17.340
It's Odysseus.

821
01:23:19.720 --> 01:23:21.600
Let him drink Odysseus.

822
01:23:22.680 --> 01:23:24.060
Then you will hear his testament.

823
01:23:39.080 --> 01:23:40.080
Odysseus?

824
01:23:40.360 --> 01:23:41.360
Yes.

825
01:23:41.740 --> 01:23:43.280
You lied to everyone.

826
01:23:47.080 --> 01:23:48.640
Did you have to lie to me?

827
01:23:50.380 --> 01:23:51.580
I needed you to believe.

828
01:23:53.280 --> 01:23:55.120
Why did you have to volunteer?

829
01:23:56.220 --> 01:23:57.780
Don't you remember how I came here?

830
01:23:57.980 --> 01:24:00.640
I begged to take Anti nous' place.

831
01:24:01.260 --> 01:24:02.260
He'd been called.

832
01:24:03.060 --> 01:24:05.720
He offered money for your
family if you'd take his place.

833
01:24:07.015 --> 01:24:08.920
If the Trojans don't let me live.

834
01:24:10.770 --> 01:24:12.340
If I never make it home.

835
01:24:13.460 --> 01:24:14.660
Take this back to my father.

836
01:24:16.550 --> 01:24:18.040
Tell him everything I did.

837
01:24:21.150 --> 01:24:22.150
Odysseus.

838
01:24:23.800 --> 01:24:26.000
Feel free to add some stuff.

839
01:24:29.265 --> 01:24:31.490
You didn't trust me with the truth?

840
01:24:33.410 --> 01:24:35.190
You knew I'd die for you.

841
01:24:35.710 --> 01:24:36.950
Dying men tell the truth.

842
01:24:37.090 --> 01:24:38.090
I needed you to believe.

843
01:24:38.790 --> 01:24:41.090
I died for your lie on that beach.

844
01:24:42.055 --> 01:24:43.055
I know.

845
01:24:43.145 --> 01:24:44.527
I was there with you.

846
01:24:44.551 --> 01:24:49.130
I heard you repeat the lie with
your dying breath. winning us the war.

847
01:24:49.850 --> 01:24:52.370
I was right there. inches
from you. smelling your blood.

848
01:24:52.550 --> 01:24:54.670
What comfort could that give me?

849
01:24:55.845 --> 01:24:59.650
Not knowing you were beside
that horse until the dead told me.

850
01:25:00.730 --> 01:25:01.730
Which dead?

851
01:25:02.190 --> 01:25:05.290
A lot of veterans of your
campaigns walk these shores.

852
01:25:07.590 --> 01:25:12.507
The dead meet to lament the
living and greet the newly dead.

853
01:25:12.531 --> 01:25:16.090
My father was the first shade to find me.

854
01:25:16.570 --> 01:25:17.570
To comfort you?

855
01:25:18.150 --> 01:25:19.150
Shades don't comfort.

856
01:25:19.930 --> 01:25:23.290
They want word of the
living who wronged them.

857
01:25:24.250 --> 01:25:31.591
My father had died in poverty. alone.
begging for scraps from people like Antinous.

858
01:25:31.830 --> 01:25:33.210
Antinous cheated you?

859
01:25:34.110 --> 01:25:35.970
As is no doubt cheating you.

860
01:25:36.470 --> 01:25:36.930
How?

861
01:25:37.310 --> 01:25:39.890
Who's an Ithaca looking
after your wife and son?

862
01:25:40.230 --> 01:25:41.650
My wife is of no concern.

863
01:25:43.190 --> 01:25:45.710
Talk to Agamemnon about homecomings.

864
01:25:47.150 --> 01:25:48.150
Agamemnon's here?

865
01:25:51.050 --> 01:25:54.570
You buried me at Troy
with respect. thank you.

866
01:25:55.284 --> 01:25:57.370
But spare a thought for those you didn't.

867
01:25:57.990 --> 01:25:59.370
It's not always possible.

868
01:26:00.550 --> 01:26:06.650
When you get home. take a ship. head
into the unknown west till you find land.

869
01:26:07.120 --> 01:26:10.570
And there. give sacrifice
and honor your men.

870
01:26:12.700 --> 01:26:14.270
Do you still have the lot?

871
01:26:18.100 --> 01:26:19.100
Of course.

872
01:26:19.780 --> 01:26:22.880
If you make it home. give
Antinous back his shame.

873
01:26:23.500 --> 01:26:24.500
I will.

874
01:26:35.470 --> 01:26:36.470
My lord.

875
01:26:48.490 --> 01:26:49.490
Odysseus.

876
01:26:49.890 --> 01:26:51.090
How are you here?

877
01:26:52.005 --> 01:26:53.790
We won the war you headed for home.

878
01:26:54.990 --> 01:26:55.990
Odysseus.

879
01:26:56.390 --> 01:26:57.910
The most brilliant of all my generals.

880
01:26:59.324 --> 01:27:01.190
He would never be snared as I was.

881
01:27:01.350 --> 01:27:02.930
When you cast the drift. like us.

882
01:27:03.730 --> 01:27:04.730
No.

883
01:27:04.895 --> 01:27:06.770
My misfortune was to make it home.

884
01:27:08.170 --> 01:27:09.930
To be welcomed by my beautiful wife.

885
01:27:16.500 --> 01:27:17.500
Bathed.

886
01:27:19.940 --> 01:27:20.940
Anointed.

887
01:27:23.360 --> 01:27:24.360
Made soft.

888
01:27:25.540 --> 01:27:30.360
To learn the hardest lesson that I'd
left to poison in her hard years before.

889
01:27:33.100 --> 01:27:35.080
Good part of her heart had gone…

890
01:27:38.360 --> 01:27:39.360
No.

891
01:27:41.420 --> 01:27:44.180
She and her lover had
plotted my murder for years.

892
01:27:45.900 --> 01:27:46.900
Odysseus.

893
01:27:47.449 --> 01:27:48.449
Yes.

894
01:27:48.900 --> 01:27:50.160
My son Orestes.

895
01:27:50.940 --> 01:27:52.000
Did he avenge me?

896
01:27:52.700 --> 01:27:53.740
My lord. how could I know?

897
01:27:54.935 --> 01:27:56.280
I'm still trying to get home.

898
01:27:57.820 --> 01:27:58.820
Don't make my mistake.

899
01:28:00.375 --> 01:28:03.120
Don't walk in the front door
expecting garlands and praise.

900
01:28:04.300 --> 01:28:05.300
Come in disguise.

901
01:28:06.174 --> 01:28:07.174
Take your time.

902
01:28:08.315 --> 01:28:09.315
Assess.

903
01:28:16.710 --> 01:28:17.710
Do you see?

904
01:28:19.150 --> 01:28:20.690
I know what I have to do.

905
01:28:21.330 --> 01:28:22.670
Some of what you have to do.

906
01:28:23.010 --> 01:28:24.790
My prophecy is not for their ears.

907
01:28:26.470 --> 01:28:27.470
Back to the ship.

908
01:28:30.090 --> 01:28:32.290
Sail southwest. past the sirens.

909
01:28:33.799 --> 01:28:36.050
Their song lures your men onto the rocks.

910
01:28:36.315 --> 01:28:37.315
They'll all die.

911
01:28:37.405 --> 01:28:38.430
I won't let that happen.

912
01:28:39.330 --> 01:28:40.330
I'll block their ears.

913
01:28:40.630 --> 01:28:41.630
With wax.

914
01:28:41.845 --> 01:28:42.845
Past the sirens.

915
01:28:43.650 --> 01:28:46.830
There's no use between the whirlpool
Charybdis and the monster Scylla.

916
01:28:47.280 --> 01:28:49.650
The whirlpool in the
sea takes all of your lives.

917
01:28:49.930 --> 01:28:50.970
The monster in the cliffs?

918
01:28:51.089 --> 01:28:52.089
Only six.

919
01:28:52.315 --> 01:28:56.610
But your determination to not sacrifice
any more lives kills all of them.

920
01:28:57.289 --> 01:28:58.710
I'll do what I have to.

921
01:28:58.950 --> 01:29:02.113
At the end. when starvation
and mutiny threaten. they

922
01:29:02.137 --> 01:29:05.030
demand to land where the
sun god grazes his cattle.

923
01:29:05.579 --> 01:29:07.310
Their slaughter Apollo's herd.

924
01:29:09.050 --> 01:29:10.390
Zeus kills them for it.

925
01:29:10.589 --> 01:29:11.590
Do you see?

926
01:29:12.630 --> 01:29:13.970
I'll stop them.

927
01:29:14.090 --> 01:29:17.710
Why do you value these men's lives
more than those you've already lost?

928
01:29:17.870 --> 01:29:19.590
I can still save them from the gods.

929
01:29:20.670 --> 01:29:22.250
But not from themselves.

930
01:29:25.050 --> 01:29:26.050
What is that?

931
01:29:26.530 --> 01:29:27.670
Your own buried crew.

932
01:29:31.430 --> 01:29:33.430
Demanding you share their dishonor.

933
01:29:35.710 --> 01:29:36.730
Let's go!

934
01:30:37.440 --> 01:30:38.117
Let's go!

935
01:30:38.141 --> 01:30:46.141
We rode out of hell.

936
01:30:51.350 --> 01:30:53.340
Leaving so many fallen comrades.

937
01:30:54.585 --> 01:30:56.000
I have to save the rest.

938
01:30:57.035 --> 01:30:58.180
What's happened to them?

939
01:30:59.080 --> 01:31:00.360
Did they leave me here?

940
01:31:00.845 --> 01:31:01.860
Are they coming back?

941
01:31:04.380 --> 01:31:05.840
Did you do something to them?

942
01:31:07.630 --> 01:31:09.020
Did you do something to them?

943
01:31:09.360 --> 01:31:10.360
Hop some.

944
01:31:10.810 --> 01:31:12.740
You told me not to eat the lotus flower.

945
01:31:13.100 --> 01:31:14.100
Just tonight.

946
01:31:14.910 --> 01:31:16.260
So you can get some sleep.

947
01:31:19.935 --> 01:31:22.770
And tomorrow. when
you're ready. you'll remember.

948
01:31:26.325 --> 01:31:27.630
You'll remember your crew.

949
01:31:28.690 --> 01:31:29.690
And your family.

950
01:31:29.930 --> 01:31:30.930
Family.

951
01:31:32.950 --> 01:31:33.950
A wife.

952
01:31:35.930 --> 01:31:36.930
Do I have a wife?

953
01:31:43.030 --> 01:31:44.040
So I'm Melanto.

954
01:31:45.055 --> 01:31:46.240
Strangers don't come in here.

955
01:31:46.645 --> 01:31:49.039
Screen or no screen.
after three years of feasting

956
01:31:49.063 --> 01:31:50.980
together. we're far
from strangers. Penelope.

957
01:31:51.185 --> 01:31:53.790
Are you trying to marry
me or ruin my reputation?

958
01:31:54.625 --> 01:31:55.720
Melanto can be discreet.

959
01:31:56.390 --> 01:31:59.540
I'm actually here out of
concern for your reputation.

960
01:31:59.980 --> 01:32:00.980
Oh?

961
01:32:01.680 --> 01:32:02.720
Please. how hard you work.

962
01:32:02.830 --> 01:32:05.080
Slow. steady progress.

963
01:32:06.580 --> 01:32:08.660
But every night. you've
been unraveling that work.

964
01:32:14.770 --> 01:32:15.770
Leave us.

965
01:32:17.225 --> 01:32:21.090
You can't expect her to be loyal
to a master she never even knew.

966
01:32:21.445 --> 01:32:23.070
I expect her to be loyal to me.

967
01:32:23.244 --> 01:32:24.244
Then she will be.

968
01:32:24.605 --> 01:32:25.605
Then you marry to me.

969
01:32:28.270 --> 01:32:30.350
Slaves have no choice but
to be loyal to the future.

970
01:32:30.755 --> 01:32:32.730
This is a household waiting for a master.

971
01:32:33.190 --> 01:32:35.190
Just as ethic as a
kingdom waiting for a king.

972
01:32:38.015 --> 01:32:39.510
Ithaca's king is coming back.

973
01:32:40.165 --> 01:32:41.165
No. he's not.

974
01:32:43.040 --> 01:32:45.630
Did you know that as a boy.
he tried to go with him to Troy?

975
01:32:47.030 --> 01:32:48.050
He never told me that.

976
01:32:49.845 --> 01:32:51.050
Dizzies refused to let me.

977
01:32:51.450 --> 01:32:54.770
He knew that Ithaca
needed a future without him.

978
01:33:01.390 --> 01:33:02.990
And he saw me as part of that future.

979
01:33:08.170 --> 01:33:10.340
I'll never tell other suitors about you.

980
01:33:12.000 --> 01:33:13.000
Deception.

981
01:33:15.850 --> 01:33:16.850
Finish your weaving.

982
01:33:19.170 --> 01:33:20.170
It's time to let him go.

983
01:33:29.905 --> 01:33:32.265
Why would you want to marry
someone who loves someone else?

984
01:33:35.475 --> 01:33:39.780
Your loyalty to Odysseus is
one of your finest qualities.

985
01:33:43.515 --> 01:33:44.515
I love you.

986
01:33:45.485 --> 01:33:48.360
I want you to choose me and end all this.

987
01:33:50.200 --> 01:33:52.280
You can't tell me you're not tired.

988
01:33:53.380 --> 01:33:54.380
The waiting.

989
01:33:54.845 --> 01:33:55.845
The uncertainty.

990
01:33:58.245 --> 01:34:00.520
You've done your duty.

991
01:34:02.060 --> 01:34:05.300
Year after year after year.

992
01:34:08.490 --> 01:34:09.730
It's time to think of yourself.

993
01:34:11.970 --> 01:34:13.000
It's time to live again.

994
01:34:18.910 --> 01:34:20.430
It's what a Dizzies would have wanted.

995
01:34:27.350 --> 01:34:28.720
I'll take care of all your needs.

996
01:34:37.720 --> 01:34:38.720
And my son?

997
01:34:40.395 --> 01:34:41.720
With thrown as he is.

998
01:34:42.345 --> 01:34:43.345
He's the heir.

999
01:34:45.820 --> 01:34:47.440
Unless we have a child of our own.

1000
01:34:57.265 --> 01:34:58.690
Where is Telemachus?

1001
01:35:00.540 --> 01:35:01.870
He's gone inland.

1002
01:35:02.655 --> 01:35:03.670
To visit his grandfather.

1003
01:35:51.386 --> 01:35:53.911
I was coming for Argus.

1004
01:35:54.266 --> 01:35:55.731
I told you that dog stays there.

1005
01:35:55.811 --> 01:35:56.811
Go back to the farm.

1006
01:35:57.091 --> 01:35:58.891
When we need your
pigs. we'll send Melantius.

1007
01:35:59.846 --> 01:36:02.091
You're no longer welcome
in this palace. old man.

1008
01:36:02.186 --> 01:36:03.851
I answer to my mistress.

1009
01:36:06.391 --> 01:36:07.631
Does she even know your name?

1010
01:36:09.411 --> 01:36:10.411
Now go!

1011
01:36:11.451 --> 01:36:14.391
Telemachus will have to come
back by the temple at Pylos.

1012
01:36:15.291 --> 01:36:16.651
You take your man away from there.

1013
01:36:17.371 --> 01:36:19.407
Why. so you can stay and
try and turn on the queen?

1014
01:36:19.431 --> 01:36:20.431
I don't think so.

1015
01:36:21.141 --> 01:36:22.551
He needs to die on that road.

1016
01:36:22.991 --> 01:36:24.471
And Eris has a plan.

1017
01:36:25.931 --> 01:36:26.931
Eris!

1018
01:36:28.726 --> 01:36:32.771
I need everyone in his party
dead. in a ditch. throats open.

1019
01:36:33.411 --> 01:36:34.899
Telemachus and his
men will be ready for the

1020
01:36:34.923 --> 01:36:37.672
bandits who work the road
between here and Pylos.

1021
01:36:38.491 --> 01:36:41.771
But if some of them took the temple
from the priests before they arrived…

1022
01:36:43.596 --> 01:36:45.211
Then bring me part of Telemachus' proof.

1023
01:36:46.951 --> 01:36:47.951
His nose.

1024
01:36:48.796 --> 01:36:50.291
Would you know him only by his nose?

1025
01:36:53.921 --> 01:36:55.301
His ears too.

1026
01:37:00.381 --> 01:37:01.491
Who taught you?

1027
01:37:02.036 --> 01:37:03.551
My father's swineherd.

1028
01:37:04.111 --> 01:37:05.111
Swineherd?

1029
01:37:05.146 --> 01:37:06.306
Your best most loyal servant.

1030
01:37:07.351 --> 01:37:09.851
Odysseus left his most
loyal servant behind.

1031
01:37:10.426 --> 01:37:11.571
He always was the smartest.

1032
01:37:12.846 --> 01:37:14.811
Only one Agamemnon I never listened to.

1033
01:37:16.071 --> 01:37:17.191
Should have listened harder.

1034
01:37:18.051 --> 01:37:19.651
Can I ask what happened to your brother?

1035
01:37:19.731 --> 01:37:21.911
His wife betrayed him and murdered him.

1036
01:37:22.951 --> 01:37:23.951
What did you do to him?

1037
01:37:23.981 --> 01:37:25.991
My son Orestes. he killed them both.

1038
01:37:26.896 --> 01:37:28.056
But he killed his own mother?

1039
01:37:29.411 --> 01:37:30.611
He avenged his father.

1040
01:37:31.656 --> 01:37:32.776
But you don't have to worry.

1041
01:37:33.091 --> 01:37:35.471
Your mother has nothing in
common with Clytemnestra.

1042
01:37:36.171 --> 01:37:37.171
Maybe not.

1043
01:37:37.411 --> 01:37:40.051
But the suitors have convinced
the elders it's time she remarried.

1044
01:37:41.161 --> 01:37:42.811
It's not a good time for an empty throne.

1045
01:37:43.691 --> 01:37:45.571
Heard the stories. people from the sea.

1046
01:37:46.236 --> 01:37:46.931
Have you been raided?

1047
01:37:47.070 --> 01:37:49.551
Not yet. but the attacks.
they do seem closer.

1048
01:37:49.910 --> 01:37:50.910
Sparta's ready.

1049
01:37:51.240 --> 01:37:52.240
What about Ithaca?

1050
01:37:53.831 --> 01:37:54.991
The army defend herself.

1051
01:37:55.251 --> 01:37:56.571
Someone's got to take the throne.

1052
01:37:56.676 --> 01:37:58.791
Then the battle is there. not here. son.

1053
01:37:59.851 --> 01:38:01.111
You've run from the problem.

1054
01:38:02.461 --> 01:38:04.611
Left your mother the mercy of the suitors.

1055
01:38:06.231 --> 01:38:07.291
Should I hire mercenaries?

1056
01:38:08.156 --> 01:38:09.331
Go back and kill them all?

1057
01:38:10.126 --> 01:38:12.871
Murder rich and powerful
guests in your own home.

1058
01:38:13.311 --> 01:38:14.311
You'll be exiled.

1059
01:38:15.191 --> 01:38:16.191
What then?

1060
01:38:16.466 --> 01:38:19.011
You must evict them
without violating Zeus' law.

1061
01:38:21.391 --> 01:38:22.751
I have to take the throne.

1062
01:38:23.911 --> 01:38:25.811
I have to know if Odysseus is alive.

1063
01:38:26.871 --> 01:38:29.111
This has nothing to do with
a father you've never known.

1064
01:38:30.271 --> 01:38:31.311
You have to lead. son.

1065
01:38:31.971 --> 01:38:33.491
No matter what's happened to Odysseus.

1066
01:38:47.501 --> 01:38:48.961
You need to remember.

1067
01:38:49.256 --> 01:38:50.256
No. I don't.

1068
01:38:51.001 --> 01:38:52.521
I don't need to know the truth.

1069
01:38:52.661 --> 01:38:54.001
I'm happy here with you.

1070
01:38:56.416 --> 01:39:00.301
And why are you gathering the
bones of your old ship to make a raft?

1071
01:39:02.861 --> 01:39:04.021
Remember your crew.

1072
01:39:05.961 --> 01:39:06.961
Your journey.

1073
01:39:11.221 --> 01:39:12.941
I heard the song of the sirens.

1074
01:39:22.781 --> 01:39:24.401
Put the wax in the men's ears.

1075
01:39:25.781 --> 01:39:26.341
None for me.

1076
01:39:26.721 --> 01:39:27.721
Tie me to the mast.

1077
01:39:27.941 --> 01:39:28.201
Why?

1078
01:39:28.701 --> 01:39:30.081
I want to hear the siren's song.

1079
01:39:30.661 --> 01:39:31.661
No.

1080
01:39:31.761 --> 01:39:32.761
That's a bad idea.

1081
01:39:33.521 --> 01:39:35.057
No one's ever heard the song and lived.

1082
01:39:35.081 --> 01:39:36.201
That's why it's a good idea.

1083
01:39:36.281 --> 01:39:37.281
I'll be the first.

1084
01:39:38.241 --> 01:39:42.121
No matter how hard I plead. do
not untie me until we're well clear.

1085
01:40:46.783 --> 01:40:48.323
What was the siren's song?

1086
01:40:50.063 --> 01:40:51.723
All the things you wanted to be.

1087
01:40:52.523 --> 01:40:56.183
Then. all the things you
wish you never wished for.

1088
01:41:13.853 --> 01:41:17.013
It was the delicious
itch you go to scratch.

1089
01:41:18.713 --> 01:41:21.453
They find it's under the
skin and you can't reach it.

1090
01:41:23.313 --> 01:41:25.893
So the delicious itch becomes unbearable.

1091
01:41:30.133 --> 01:41:36.573
I told you what you most want
is what you most can't have.

1092
01:41:40.043 --> 01:41:46.483
And what you most can't have
is what you already had and lost.

1093
01:41:55.353 --> 01:41:58.033
It was the song of all the
promises I failed to keep.

1094
01:42:03.123 --> 01:42:05.943
And it told me I don't
really want to go home.

1095
01:42:10.353 --> 01:42:11.813
My water ahead!

1096
01:42:14.613 --> 01:42:15.613
Charybdis.

1097
01:42:16.953 --> 01:42:18.313
The monstrous whirlpool.

1098
01:42:21.413 --> 01:42:22.413
Hoist the sails!

1099
01:42:22.733 --> 01:42:23.733
Come on. let's go!

1100
01:42:24.193 --> 01:42:25.333
Get the whirlpool shot!

1101
01:42:26.213 --> 01:42:27.213
Can we head out to sea?

1102
01:42:27.333 --> 01:42:28.373
It's already got us.

1103
01:42:30.773 --> 01:42:31.773
Get in the boat!

1104
01:42:32.453 --> 01:42:33.553
The water hammer is moving!

1105
01:42:35.153 --> 01:42:36.513
We might make that canyon.

1106
01:42:36.693 --> 01:42:37.693
It's too narrow.

1107
01:42:38.213 --> 01:42:39.213
Make for the whirlpool.

1108
01:42:39.733 --> 01:42:43.353
If you steer down the slope. we can make
enough weight to shoot out the other side.

1109
01:42:43.793 --> 01:42:45.233
Don't be afraid. we can do it.

1110
01:42:50.383 --> 01:42:51.383
No.

1111
01:42:51.463 --> 01:42:52.463
No!

1112
01:42:52.763 --> 01:42:53.923
We're making for the channel.

1113
01:42:54.463 --> 01:42:55.683
We're making for the channel!

1114
01:42:56.343 --> 01:42:57.343
Oars in!

1115
01:42:58.963 --> 01:43:00.423
Get the oars in!

1116
01:43:00.883 --> 01:43:01.883
It's over an oars!

1117
01:43:02.183 --> 01:43:03.363
Prepare to hold water!

1118
01:43:06.003 --> 01:43:12.073
On my signal!

1119
01:43:13.533 --> 01:43:14.533
Three…

1120
01:43:19.473 --> 01:43:20.793
Four…

1121
01:43:21.113 --> 01:43:22.113
Three!

1122
01:44:07.498 --> 01:44:09.533
We made it!

1123
01:44:10.293 --> 01:44:11.893
We did it!

1124
01:44:12.073 --> 01:44:13.234
We did it!

1125
01:44:13.258 --> 01:44:14.258
You guys…

1126
01:44:24.133 --> 01:44:25.973
Keep us straight!

1127
01:44:33.123 --> 01:44:35.063
Keep us straight!

1128
01:45:01.623 --> 01:45:02.623
You knew!

1129
01:45:03.623 --> 01:45:04.663
And you didn't tell us!

1130
01:45:05.283 --> 01:45:07.563
If I told you. you wouldn't
have chosen this way.

1131
01:45:07.923 --> 01:45:10.143
And those men would still be alive!

1132
01:45:10.523 --> 01:45:10.523
No!

1133
01:45:10.903 --> 01:45:11.903
We'd all be dead!

1134
01:45:12.403 --> 01:45:13.403
You had no right!

1135
01:45:13.638 --> 01:45:14.643
I had every right!

1136
01:45:15.083 --> 01:45:16.543
And every responsibility!

1137
01:45:17.203 --> 01:45:19.903
The whirlpool would have
destroyed the ship and all of us!

1138
01:45:20.363 --> 01:45:21.363
This way we live!

1139
01:45:21.583 --> 01:45:22.583
Some of us live!

1140
01:45:22.723 --> 01:45:23.723
Yes!

1141
01:45:26.903 --> 01:45:28.783
What else did Tiresias tell you?

1142
01:45:40.473 --> 01:45:42.533
I'm going to put in there…

1143
01:45:44.333 --> 01:45:45.993
We can't land there!

1144
01:45:46.193 --> 01:45:47.593
That's the sun god's isle!

1145
01:45:48.053 --> 01:45:49.053
We need repairs!

1146
01:45:50.473 --> 01:45:51.953
These men are exhausted!

1147
01:45:52.553 --> 01:45:53.653
I want six shipmates!

1148
01:45:54.393 --> 01:45:56.873
I'm going to put in… I'm
going to rest up on dry land.

1149
01:45:57.233 --> 01:45:58.293
You're all going to die!

1150
01:46:01.493 --> 01:46:03.533
You asked me what Tiresias told me.

1151
01:46:04.503 --> 01:46:05.833
He said you're all going to die.

1152
01:46:06.433 --> 01:46:13.434
If you slaughter the sun god's cattle
which graze on that island. you'll all die.

1153
01:46:16.933 --> 01:46:17.963
That's fine.

1154
01:46:18.648 --> 01:46:20.003
We'll put in.

1155
01:46:21.153 --> 01:46:22.403
We'll cook our own provisions.

1156
01:46:22.708 --> 01:46:23.483
We'll pick fruit.

1157
01:46:23.623 --> 01:46:24.243
We'll get water.

1158
01:46:24.603 --> 01:46:25.603
Nothing more.

1159
01:46:26.943 --> 01:46:27.943
Swear to it.

1160
01:46:28.643 --> 01:46:29.643
All of you.

1161
01:46:43.463 --> 01:46:44.463
See?

1162
01:46:45.723 --> 01:46:47.103
The wind took us right in.

1163
01:46:48.343 --> 01:46:49.783
We'll rest up…

1164
01:46:50.283 --> 01:46:53.083
Do the repairs and set out
as soon as the wind changes.

1165
01:46:54.463 --> 01:46:55.463
Grab that light!

1166
01:47:06.303 --> 01:47:07.963
Did the crew keep their promise?

1167
01:47:09.503 --> 01:47:10.503
Yes.

1168
01:47:11.063 --> 01:47:12.363
For a long time.

1169
01:47:14.178 --> 01:47:15.763
But the wind never changed.

1170
01:47:16.223 --> 01:47:21.740
The steady onshore breeze
that made it so easy for us to land

1171
01:47:21.764 --> 01:47:23.943
made it impossible to leave.

1172
01:47:28.053 --> 01:47:29.853
And our provisions ran out.

1173
01:47:33.033 --> 01:47:34.033
Go!

1174
01:48:36.473 --> 01:48:39.593
Did you think if you ate quietly
the sun god wouldn't notice?

1175
01:48:40.373 --> 01:48:41.613
We thought you wouldn't notice.

1176
01:48:42.588 --> 01:48:43.673
I'm not the problem.

1177
01:48:44.118 --> 01:48:45.133
I wanted you to live.

1178
01:48:51.373 --> 01:48:52.393
Tiresias told you.

1179
01:48:52.973 --> 01:48:53.633
Cersei told you.

1180
01:48:53.713 --> 01:48:54.713
The gods told you.

1181
01:48:55.793 --> 01:48:57.813
You gods don't speak
in ways we understand.

1182
01:48:58.233 --> 01:48:59.553
Who doesn't understand pain?

1183
01:49:00.493 --> 01:49:01.833
Or blood or death?

1184
01:49:02.533 --> 01:49:05.673
When you watch your men die. do you
see chance or do you see consequence?

1185
01:49:06.733 --> 01:49:07.733
I see consequence.

1186
01:49:08.133 --> 01:49:09.133
I see my failure.

1187
01:49:09.953 --> 01:49:11.389
What if their deaths aren't your failure?

1188
01:49:11.413 --> 01:49:13.453
I lead them.

1189
01:49:15.073 --> 01:49:16.133
I led them here.

1190
01:49:17.053 --> 01:49:18.053
And who led you?

1191
01:49:19.413 --> 01:49:20.973
Why do you put yourself above the gods?

1192
01:49:21.113 --> 01:49:22.493
Why do you claim responsibility?

1193
01:49:23.813 --> 01:49:25.133
Why don't you want to go home?

1194
01:49:25.683 --> 01:49:26.683
What do you expect?

1195
01:49:28.428 --> 01:49:29.973
They ran out of food!

1196
01:49:31.108 --> 01:49:32.173
Have some pity.

1197
01:49:32.353 --> 01:49:35.153
My pity is what put
us on this damn island.

1198
01:49:35.493 --> 01:49:36.653
I told you what would happen.

1199
01:49:36.973 --> 01:49:37.973
Yes. you did.

1200
01:49:38.413 --> 01:49:41.233
And we decided we would
rather drown than starve.

1201
01:49:47.213 --> 01:49:49.033
Well. now's our chance.

1202
01:49:49.558 --> 01:49:50.633
The wind has dropped!

1203
01:49:50.843 --> 01:49:51.853
The wind has dropped!

1204
01:49:55.213 --> 01:49:59.253
The calm was just long enough to
lure us out onto Poseidon's ocean.

1205
01:50:00.843 --> 01:50:01.843
Under Zeus' sky.

1206
01:50:03.553 --> 01:50:04.853
Stay off!

1207
01:50:05.693 --> 01:50:06.693
It's too late!

1208
01:50:07.173 --> 01:50:08.173
Hurry go!

1209
01:50:10.013 --> 01:50:11.013
Hurry go!

1210
01:50:12.493 --> 01:50:13.553
Hold on!

1211
01:50:20.333 --> 01:50:23.413
The wind has just stopped!

1212
01:50:24.973 --> 01:50:25.973
Hurry!

1213
01:50:27.233 --> 01:50:35.233
My wind!

1214
01:51:53.543 --> 01:51:56.903
The last thing I remember
was the harsh hand of Zeus.

1215
01:52:41.362 --> 01:52:43.543
I don't know what happened to my men.

1216
01:52:44.023 --> 01:52:45.123
Yes you do.

1217
01:52:46.823 --> 01:52:48.463
Exactly what you told them what happened.

1218
01:52:49.293 --> 01:52:51.063
I washed up on your shore alone.

1219
01:52:51.703 --> 01:52:56.103
You washed up on my shore with
some of your boat and none of your crew.

1220
01:52:57.843 --> 01:53:00.023
Half dead. unconscious.

1221
01:53:23.043 --> 01:53:28.453
I watched you lost for days into weeks.

1222
01:53:29.753 --> 01:53:33.018
I knew the lotus would
ease your awakening so

1223
01:53:33.042 --> 01:53:36.574
that your pain was more
of the body than the mind.

1224
01:53:38.853 --> 01:53:39.993
And it did.

1225
01:53:43.073 --> 01:53:44.353
You liked it so much.

1226
01:53:45.628 --> 01:53:47.533
You ate it so willingly.

1227
01:53:51.613 --> 01:53:52.833
And as I cared for you.

1228
01:53:53.533 --> 01:53:54.533
Thank you.

1229
01:53:54.918 --> 01:53:56.013
I came to love you.

1230
01:54:01.718 --> 01:54:03.083
How long have I been here?

1231
01:54:05.668 --> 01:54:08.183
I kept telling myself
to stop giving it to you.

1232
01:54:08.393 --> 01:54:10.063
That you were strong enough to remember.

1233
01:54:10.323 --> 01:54:11.199
How long. Calypso?

1234
01:54:11.223 --> 01:54:12.463
But you were so happy.

1235
01:54:12.703 --> 01:54:13.383
You were happy.

1236
01:54:13.543 --> 01:54:15.063
We were so happy.

1237
01:54:15.413 --> 01:54:16.413
For years.

1238
01:54:16.723 --> 01:54:17.723
Years?

1239
01:54:23.968 --> 01:54:25.143
Seven years.

1240
01:54:26.493 --> 01:54:29.883
You fed me lotus flower
and held me captive.

1241
01:54:30.133 --> 01:54:31.463
I saved your life.

1242
01:54:32.663 --> 01:54:33.683
I rebuilt your body.

1243
01:54:33.883 --> 01:54:36.443
I just couldn't bring
myself to rebuild your mind.

1244
01:54:37.732 --> 01:54:39.123
You have been happy.

1245
01:54:40.298 --> 01:54:43.203
Your heart was just always somewhere else.

1246
01:54:44.703 --> 01:54:47.683
And your mind was
bound to follow eventually.

1247
01:54:49.243 --> 01:54:49.920
How could you?

1248
01:54:49.944 --> 01:54:53.720
The lotus clouds the
mind and stops the well.

1249
01:54:53.744 --> 01:54:55.703
But it doesn't change who you are.

1250
01:54:56.463 --> 01:54:59.243
You weren't ready to go
home for whatever reason.

1251
01:54:59.803 --> 01:55:00.803
I am now.

1252
01:55:02.203 --> 01:55:04.223
As I always knew you would be.

1253
01:55:05.223 --> 01:55:05.383
Now?

1254
01:55:05.903 --> 01:55:08.543
You were clutching
something when I found you.

1255
01:55:08.883 --> 01:55:10.463
Your hand wouldn't open for weeks.

1256
01:55:11.383 --> 01:55:12.543
You'd call out.

1257
01:55:13.563 --> 01:55:17.503
Mostly to Athena. but sometimes
you would say another name.

1258
01:55:36.783 --> 01:55:38.403
Help me go home.

1259
01:55:39.443 --> 01:55:40.443
I am.

1260
01:55:41.363 --> 01:55:43.703
You're a man who
needs to control his fate.

1261
01:55:45.103 --> 01:55:46.843
But you cannot control this.

1262
01:55:50.263 --> 01:55:52.163
You must give yourself to the storm.

1263
01:55:53.143 --> 01:55:54.580
Give yourself to Poseidon.

1264
01:55:54.604 --> 01:55:57.603
And take your punishment.

1265
01:55:59.683 --> 01:56:02.483
I just won't let him kill you.

1266
01:56:05.523 --> 01:56:08.983
Give up the fight.
give up control and live.

1267
01:56:11.903 --> 01:56:15.823
It's a leap of faith you've
never yet made Odysseus.

1268
01:57:08.113 --> 01:57:09.113
Odysseus.

1269
01:57:17.223 --> 01:57:18.223
Where am I?

1270
01:57:20.323 --> 01:57:22.163
Don't you recognize your own home?

1271
01:58:01.313 --> 01:58:03.033
Zeus welcomes you. strangers.

1272
01:58:04.078 --> 01:58:05.393
How many are you?

1273
01:58:06.208 --> 01:58:07.208
Half a dozen.

1274
01:58:07.647 --> 01:58:08.647
In need of a meal?

1275
01:58:09.193 --> 01:58:10.193
And supplies.

1276
01:58:10.753 --> 01:58:11.753
For the road.

1277
01:58:12.453 --> 01:58:13.453
Where are you headed?

1278
01:58:13.653 --> 01:58:14.653
We need pigs.

1279
01:58:15.113 --> 01:58:16.493
We're going all the way to Pylos.

1280
01:58:17.093 --> 01:58:18.093
Are you pilgrims?

1281
01:58:19.273 --> 01:58:20.493
Do we look like pilgrims?

1282
01:58:21.003 --> 01:58:22.073
I don't see well.

1283
01:58:23.473 --> 01:58:26.953
Zeus demands I offer you a meal.
but these pigs aren't mine to sell.

1284
01:58:27.373 --> 01:58:28.373
Oh. don't worry.

1285
01:58:28.993 --> 01:58:29.993
We're not paying.

1286
01:58:33.228 --> 01:58:35.293
Give my greetings to your mother.

1287
01:58:38.808 --> 01:58:39.833
Tell her I'm sorry.

1288
01:58:40.543 --> 01:58:42.969
I'm sorry for Troy
and for everything that.

1289
01:58:50.734 --> 01:58:52.553
I'm sorry I had no news of your father.

1290
01:58:53.008 --> 01:58:54.008
No. you had news.

1291
01:58:54.683 --> 01:58:56.693
Not of where he is. but who he is.

1292
01:58:57.973 --> 01:59:00.353
And now more than ever. I
hope to one day meet him.

1293
01:59:05.583 --> 01:59:07.363
Where are your watchdogs. old man?

1294
01:59:11.988 --> 01:59:13.643
I'm burning their bodies.

1295
01:59:18.628 --> 01:59:20.910
Can Zeus offer you
food and drink. stranger?

1296
01:59:20.934 --> 01:59:22.953
Were you attacked?

1297
01:59:24.043 --> 01:59:25.433
The dogs saved your farmhands.

1298
01:59:25.958 --> 01:59:27.933
Oh. we burned his brothers first.

1299
01:59:31.233 --> 01:59:32.253
What happened to Ithaca?

1300
01:59:33.272 --> 01:59:34.272
Darkness.

1301
01:59:34.568 --> 01:59:36.833
Zeus's law smashed to pieces.

1302
01:59:37.838 --> 01:59:40.873
A kingdom without a
king since my master died.

1303
01:59:41.298 --> 01:59:42.298
Your master?

1304
01:59:43.403 --> 01:59:44.403
Odysseus.

1305
01:59:45.263 --> 01:59:46.513
Hero of the Trojan War.

1306
01:59:49.173 --> 01:59:50.433
But Odysseus is alive.

1307
01:59:50.878 --> 01:59:53.733
No more!

1308
01:59:54.133 --> 01:59:54.653
No more!

1309
01:59:55.028 --> 01:59:56.033
No more!

1310
01:59:59.213 --> 02:00:00.213
Telemachus.

1311
02:00:01.353 --> 02:00:02.353
Telemachus.

1312
02:00:04.643 --> 02:00:06.513
He's in danger and I can't help him.

1313
02:00:06.918 --> 02:00:10.373
There must be others in Ithaca
that would help Odysseus's son.

1314
02:00:10.613 --> 02:00:12.593
How is this controlled by suitors?

1315
02:00:13.458 --> 02:00:15.773
No one is still loyal to Odysseus.

1316
02:00:17.193 --> 02:00:18.193
What about the queen?

1317
02:00:19.963 --> 02:00:21.093
Beautiful. wise Penelope.

1318
02:00:22.243 --> 02:00:24.473
Held hostage by the worst men.

1319
02:00:24.903 --> 02:00:26.813
Soon to be forced into marriage.

1320
02:00:26.973 --> 02:00:28.993
What could she do without even her son?

1321
02:00:29.498 --> 02:00:30.498
Here. drink.

1322
02:00:35.673 --> 02:00:37.053
What's the danger to Telemachus?

1323
02:00:38.193 --> 02:00:40.513
He's on his way back from Sparta.

1324
02:00:41.518 --> 02:00:45.913
The suitors send bandits to
Pylos to ambush him at the temple.

1325
02:00:46.977 --> 02:00:48.053
Give me food for the road.

1326
02:00:48.948 --> 02:00:51.553
You'll never catch up with the bandits.

1327
02:00:52.048 --> 02:00:55.393
If I can get to Pylos before
Telemachus arrives. I can warn him.

1328
02:00:55.778 --> 02:00:56.893
Why are you helping?

1329
02:00:58.123 --> 02:00:59.693
If I tell you. don't be angry.

1330
02:01:00.383 --> 02:01:02.293
I served with Odysseus at Troy.

1331
02:01:02.593 --> 02:01:03.593
Really?

1332
02:01:04.813 --> 02:01:06.193
He was a harsh taskmaster.

1333
02:01:06.813 --> 02:01:07.813
But fair.

1334
02:01:09.063 --> 02:01:10.953
Fair and worthy of following.

1335
02:01:12.543 --> 02:01:13.543
You loved him.

1336
02:01:14.393 --> 02:01:15.393
Like a son?

1337
02:01:16.423 --> 02:01:18.733
Well. he's not dead.

1338
02:01:19.313 --> 02:01:20.853
Is she coming home?

1339
02:01:22.093 --> 02:01:23.093
Soon.

1340
02:01:23.538 --> 02:01:24.538
Bringing vengeance?

1341
02:01:27.108 --> 02:01:28.333
Bringing it all.

1342
02:01:38.003 --> 02:01:39.003
Don't talk.

1343
02:01:39.063 --> 02:01:40.783
We don't want people
realizing who you are.

1344
02:01:41.123 --> 02:01:42.963
Well. maybe we shouldn't
have brought a guard.

1345
02:01:43.183 --> 02:01:45.263
We'll be glad we did if we
have trouble on the road.

1346
02:02:05.303 --> 02:02:07.343
Find that beggar.

1347
02:02:22.523 --> 02:02:24.083
Your men must wait out here.

1348
02:02:24.543 --> 02:02:25.543
The weapons too.

1349
02:02:42.523 --> 02:02:43.893
Zeus welcomes you strangers.

1350
02:02:44.658 --> 02:02:45.658
Have you traveled far?

1351
02:02:46.232 --> 02:02:47.232
Not that far.

1352
02:02:48.588 --> 02:02:50.353
You're here to rest for the night.

1353
02:02:52.513 --> 02:02:54.573
We're here to make sacrifice to Athena.

1354
02:02:56.793 --> 02:02:59.773
And whatever hospitality you
can offer might be considered.

1355
02:03:00.313 --> 02:03:01.313
Of course.

1356
02:03:01.373 --> 02:03:02.533
Get that beggar out of here.

1357
02:03:02.653 --> 02:03:04.033
He has a message for me.

1358
02:03:04.938 --> 02:03:06.133
You may have sent you.

1359
02:03:07.408 --> 02:03:08.408
Yes. sir.

1360
02:03:14.263 --> 02:03:15.423
But what's the message?

1361
02:03:17.223 --> 02:03:18.223
He's private.

1362
02:03:18.743 --> 02:03:19.883
He's a man of pri…

1363
02:03:21.383 --> 02:03:22.383
He's a man of praise.

1364
02:03:39.423 --> 02:03:42.113
This is your moment to leave. old man.

1365
02:03:42.953 --> 02:03:43.953
Go. stranger.

1366
02:03:46.173 --> 02:03:48.473
I already spared one old man this week.

1367
02:03:49.113 --> 02:03:50.113
But he was blind.

1368
02:03:50.993 --> 02:03:51.993
I won't spare…

1369
02:04:07.593 --> 02:04:08.593
No!

1370
02:04:30.643 --> 02:04:32.223
It's not bad for a beggar.

1371
02:04:32.923 --> 02:04:34.223
No one's born a beggar.

1372
02:04:35.123 --> 02:04:36.363
We'll take this priest's robes.

1373
02:04:36.983 --> 02:04:37.983
Put them over your armor.

1374
02:04:40.183 --> 02:04:41.363
Help me with his body.

1375
02:04:41.703 --> 02:04:42.703
We have to leave him.

1376
02:04:43.183 --> 02:04:43.503
No.

1377
02:04:43.763 --> 02:04:44.843
We have to slip out.

1378
02:04:45.703 --> 02:04:47.063
That's not how you honor the dead.

1379
02:04:47.243 --> 02:04:48.483
That is how you stay alive.

1380
02:04:48.663 --> 02:04:49.663
He was my teacher.

1381
02:04:51.143 --> 02:04:52.639
He might have been Athena in disguise.

1382
02:04:52.663 --> 02:04:53.783
His name was Mentor.

1383
02:04:54.663 --> 02:04:57.263
And when you are safe. we'll
travel to the unknown west.

1384
02:04:57.943 --> 02:04:59.043
And we will honor him.

1385
02:04:59.643 --> 02:05:01.040
These men were sent by the suitors.

1386
02:05:01.064 --> 02:05:03.643
There will be more of them
we need to get on the road.

1387
02:05:04.143 --> 02:05:04.563
By night?

1388
02:05:05.123 --> 02:05:06.163
Safer than staying here.

1389
02:05:06.783 --> 02:05:08.723
Mentor's at the heart of
Athena's oldest temple.

1390
02:05:09.543 --> 02:05:11.523
For now. we'll honor him in flame.

1391
02:05:50.663 --> 02:05:52.303
So how does a beggar come to know Mentor?

1392
02:05:52.513 --> 02:05:53.513
I told you.

1393
02:05:53.723 --> 02:05:54.883
I wasn't always a beggar.

1394
02:05:55.482 --> 02:05:56.723
You have wise eyes.

1395
02:05:57.903 --> 02:05:59.763
Athena's eyes… Don't
look for gods in men.

1396
02:06:00.112 --> 02:06:01.383
You'll just be disappointed.

1397
02:06:01.768 --> 02:06:03.463
Well. then tell me who you are.

1398
02:06:05.293 --> 02:06:06.443
My name is Sinon.

1399
02:06:07.083 --> 02:06:10.023
I'm an old soldier who fought
under your father at Troy.

1400
02:06:11.218 --> 02:06:12.363
You knew my father?

1401
02:06:12.958 --> 02:06:15.963
I've been taking orders from him
for longer than I care to remember.

1402
02:06:17.243 --> 02:06:18.243
Wait. he's alive?

1403
02:06:19.303 --> 02:06:20.303
He's alive.

1404
02:06:21.913 --> 02:06:23.083
Well. where is he?

1405
02:06:23.753 --> 02:06:24.753
He's close by.

1406
02:06:25.433 --> 02:06:27.663
He sent me ahead to assess the situation.

1407
02:06:29.378 --> 02:06:31.023
Well. Mother's not gonna believe it.

1408
02:06:31.158 --> 02:06:32.343
No. you can't tell her.

1409
02:06:33.783 --> 02:06:34.783
What. nothing?

1410
02:06:35.763 --> 02:06:36.763
Tell her.

1411
02:06:37.983 --> 02:06:40.363
Tell her he decided
it's time she remarried.

1412
02:06:42.343 --> 02:06:43.803
He doesn't need to test my mother.

1413
02:06:43.903 --> 02:06:44.903
How can he doubt her?

1414
02:06:45.003 --> 02:06:46.003
He doesn't.

1415
02:06:46.363 --> 02:06:48.643
But she has every reason
to have forgotten him.

1416
02:06:50.458 --> 02:06:52.083
Are there any loyal servants?

1417
02:06:53.583 --> 02:06:54.583
Some.

1418
02:06:55.303 --> 02:06:56.943
Why. Odysseus shows himself all.

1419
02:06:58.823 --> 02:07:00.623
We need to gather
the suitors at the palace.

1420
02:07:01.813 --> 02:07:02.863
That's never a problem.

1421
02:07:03.683 --> 02:07:04.963
You have gifts for Menelaus?

1422
02:07:05.743 --> 02:07:06.743
Yeah. on my ship.

1423
02:07:07.543 --> 02:07:08.543
Good.

1424
02:07:08.863 --> 02:07:09.863
Come back as a prince.

1425
02:07:10.368 --> 02:07:11.368
Call a banquet.

1426
02:07:12.063 --> 02:07:13.063
I'll be there.

1427
02:07:13.918 --> 02:07:15.423
What will you do at the banquet?

1428
02:07:16.583 --> 02:07:17.583
Beg.

1429
02:07:17.798 --> 02:07:19.743
The clearest view of a man is from below.

1430
02:07:21.783 --> 02:07:23.223
How many suitors are there?

1431
02:07:24.383 --> 02:07:25.383
Dozens.

1432
02:07:25.718 --> 02:07:28.563
If all of his men are like you.
then… He doesn't have any men.

1433
02:07:29.698 --> 02:07:30.698
But it's just you?

1434
02:07:31.677 --> 02:07:32.823
And you.

1435
02:07:39.123 --> 02:07:40.323
Telemachus is back.

1436
02:07:40.583 --> 02:07:40.763
What?

1437
02:07:40.903 --> 02:07:41.903
Telemachus is back.

1438
02:07:42.703 --> 02:07:43.703
Who's saying this?

1439
02:07:44.083 --> 02:07:46.543
Everyone's the… Where's Telemachus?

1440
02:07:47.323 --> 02:07:48.323
My queen!

1441
02:07:48.623 --> 02:07:50.003
Surely your place is up there.

1442
02:07:58.223 --> 02:07:59.223
Is it true?

1443
02:08:01.943 --> 02:08:03.023
Leave her home.

1444
02:08:04.083 --> 02:08:05.083
I'm back.

1445
02:08:05.498 --> 02:08:07.223
I thought tonight we could celebrate.

1446
02:08:08.323 --> 02:08:11.243
If we have anything
left to celebrate with.

1447
02:08:12.783 --> 02:08:13.783
Don't worry.

1448
02:08:14.393 --> 02:08:17.223
My brave suitors will shower us
with gifts to honor your return.

1449
02:08:17.763 --> 02:08:19.123
So glad to see your safe return.

1450
02:08:30.113 --> 02:08:31.413
Glad to see you on your feet.

1451
02:08:32.098 --> 02:08:33.993
It's about time we took
you back to the palace.

1452
02:08:37.973 --> 02:08:39.413
What did you hear about your father?

1453
02:08:41.323 --> 02:08:42.323
Nothing.

1454
02:08:43.213 --> 02:08:46.463
A story is from the war. but no one knew
what happened to him after he left Troy.

1455
02:08:47.343 --> 02:08:48.343
I'm sorry. Mom.

1456
02:08:49.458 --> 02:08:52.263
Everyone in Sparta is talking
about a coming catastrophe.

1457
02:08:53.973 --> 02:08:57.743
An age of darkness brought on by
people from the sea. violating Zeus' law.

1458
02:08:57.928 --> 02:08:59.023
Some stories are true.

1459
02:08:59.278 --> 02:09:00.963
Our civilization is collapsing.

1460
02:09:01.588 --> 02:09:04.428
Menelaus is concerned that we can't
raise an army with an empty throne.

1461
02:09:05.003 --> 02:09:06.083
So we came up with a plan.

1462
02:09:07.783 --> 02:09:08.783
What plan?

1463
02:09:11.173 --> 02:09:12.803
The one way to get the suitors to leave.

1464
02:09:15.473 --> 02:09:16.663
It's time for you to choose.

1465
02:09:20.668 --> 02:09:21.853
You want me to remarry?

1466
02:09:22.373 --> 02:09:25.133
If you remarry. the
other suitors will leave.

1467
02:09:25.498 --> 02:09:27.218
And then I'm only
dealing with one of them.

1468
02:09:27.518 --> 02:09:28.518
I'm almost of age.

1469
02:09:28.573 --> 02:09:31.753
I'll tell the elders that I learned
of a deceased's death in Sparta.

1470
02:09:32.593 --> 02:09:35.433
Menelaus will back me up and
they'll let me assume the throne.

1471
02:09:35.613 --> 02:09:39.013
So you deny your father and I leave my
home and go live with one of these snakes.

1472
02:09:39.193 --> 02:09:40.193
That's your plan.

1473
02:09:40.363 --> 02:09:41.483
Would you have a better one?

1474
02:09:44.168 --> 02:09:47.513
Lock the door. set a fire.
and burn the bastards.

1475
02:09:48.848 --> 02:09:52.293
Do you think if I remarry. life
goes back to the way it was?

1476
02:09:53.553 --> 02:09:55.033
That world is gone.

1477
02:09:55.373 --> 02:09:59.810
And in this one. they're not
giving up power to you or Odysseus.

1478
02:09:59.834 --> 02:10:02.173
If he returned. he'd have to kill him.

1479
02:10:02.333 --> 02:10:03.333
Like you will.

1480
02:10:04.423 --> 02:10:07.313
If I kill them. their families
will demand revenge.

1481
02:10:07.533 --> 02:10:08.533
I'd be exiled.

1482
02:10:09.723 --> 02:10:11.513
And without me. the throne will be lost.

1483
02:10:11.733 --> 02:10:13.373
Because only a man can sit on it.

1484
02:10:14.988 --> 02:10:16.033
Empty throne?

1485
02:10:17.698 --> 02:10:20.573
I've been sitting on that
empty throne for 20 years!

1486
02:10:21.338 --> 02:10:24.391
My knowledge. my years
of experience. that's all

1487
02:10:24.415 --> 02:10:26.774
nothing compared to
the bristles on your chin.

1488
02:10:29.813 --> 02:10:30.813
Do you want peace?

1489
02:10:31.973 --> 02:10:32.973
Or do you want revenge?

1490
02:10:33.153 --> 02:10:33.810
I want Odysseus!

1491
02:10:33.834 --> 02:10:34.834
Dance!

1492
02:10:37.633 --> 02:10:40.433
Sing. muse of a face!

1493
02:10:43.773 --> 02:10:44.793
A face!

1494
02:10:48.793 --> 02:10:50.233
A fleet!

1495
02:10:55.013 --> 02:10:56.013
A war!

1496
02:11:00.313 --> 02:11:01.313
At Troy!

1497
02:11:05.673 --> 02:11:07.293
Sing. muse of a man!

1498
02:11:11.513 --> 02:11:12.513
A man!

1499
02:11:17.753 --> 02:11:18.753
At Troy!

1500
02:11:27.123 --> 02:11:28.623
You may as well go ahead.

1501
02:11:36.923 --> 02:11:37.923
Odysseus.

1502
02:11:59.308 --> 02:12:00.788
You should bury him up on the cliffs.

1503
02:12:02.878 --> 02:12:03.963
Where you met.

1504
02:12:12.663 --> 02:12:14.153
You're Odysseus.

1505
02:12:17.723 --> 02:12:18.723
You're my father.

1506
02:12:21.413 --> 02:12:22.713
I'm a beggar.

1507
02:12:26.183 --> 02:12:27.293
And you

1508
02:12:29.513 --> 02:12:30.593
are the worthy

1509
02:12:32.238 --> 02:12:34.853
beautiful son of Odysseus.

1510
02:12:36.803 --> 02:12:37.803
Of whom

1511
02:12:38.363 --> 02:12:39.713
when you do finally meet.

1512
02:12:42.153 --> 02:12:43.793
He will be so proud.

1513
02:12:48.163 --> 02:12:50.564
Welcome home… stranger.

1514
02:12:53.333 --> 02:12:55.523
Because the darkness of victory

1515
02:12:56.803 --> 02:12:58.263
shrouds the rightest of legends.

1516
02:13:00.243 --> 02:13:03.183
And make bars the blind beggars of us all.

1517
02:13:10.353 --> 02:13:12.623
Accept the hospitality of Zeus.

1518
02:13:13.523 --> 02:13:14.663
Get the strangers some food.

1519
02:13:15.403 --> 02:13:16.403
No. sir.

1520
02:13:16.963 --> 02:13:18.683
I'll just make their ends with a bowl.

1521
02:13:24.403 --> 02:13:26.883
Had to invite another one of
these filthy plate lickers today.

1522
02:13:27.343 --> 02:13:28.923
What's one more beggar at this feast?

1523
02:13:47.343 --> 02:13:50.143
We need to kill him before he ever
gains his position with the elders.

1524
02:13:50.203 --> 02:13:51.203
How?

1525
02:14:09.293 --> 02:14:10.993
Get him to grab one of the weapons.

1526
02:14:15.533 --> 02:14:17.953
Isn't that the same
young pup you used to be?

1527
02:14:18.513 --> 02:14:20.913
When we come back
tonight. let me cut his tongue.

1528
02:14:22.413 --> 02:14:23.413
Fuck off. Olaf.

1529
02:14:23.753 --> 02:14:24.753
Please.

1530
02:14:24.993 --> 02:14:26.129
It's been days since I've eaten.

1531
02:14:26.153 --> 02:14:27.373
I told you to fuck off.

1532
02:14:27.433 --> 02:14:30.273
You can't be generous with
food that's not even yours.

1533
02:14:32.333 --> 02:14:33.773
There's no room in your bowl.

1534
02:14:34.393 --> 02:14:35.473
Yes. there is.

1535
02:14:41.083 --> 02:14:42.083
So there is.

1536
02:14:43.743 --> 02:14:44.843
There you go.

1537
02:14:48.763 --> 02:14:50.743
I suppose you want something from me now.

1538
02:14:50.943 --> 02:14:51.943
No.

1539
02:14:52.363 --> 02:14:54.103
I have something for you.

1540
02:14:55.323 --> 02:14:56.403
You have something from me?

1541
02:14:57.623 --> 02:14:58.923
You have something from me!

1542
02:15:00.603 --> 02:15:06.943
What could a filthy old plate licker
like you possibly have that I could want?

1543
02:15:08.103 --> 02:15:09.783
Actually. it's yours.

1544
02:15:15.183 --> 02:15:17.443
I was asked to return it.

1545
02:15:19.143 --> 02:15:20.283
It's not mine.

1546
02:15:22.343 --> 02:15:23.343
No.

1547
02:15:26.773 --> 02:15:27.773
Where did you get this?

1548
02:15:30.253 --> 02:15:32.213
Don't turn your back on me!

1549
02:15:37.623 --> 02:15:38.623
Continuous.

1550
02:15:39.483 --> 02:15:40.799
You can't treat a beggar like that.

1551
02:15:40.823 --> 02:15:41.823
It's Zeus's law.

1552
02:15:42.763 --> 02:15:43.763
Zeus's law?

1553
02:15:47.603 --> 02:15:49.183
You think this is a god?

1554
02:15:52.483 --> 02:15:54.503
You think this is a god in disguise?

1555
02:15:55.923 --> 02:15:56.923
Are you?

1556
02:15:58.403 --> 02:15:59.523
Are you a god?

1557
02:16:01.283 --> 02:16:02.283
A plate licker?

1558
02:16:03.123 --> 02:16:04.123
No.

1559
02:16:04.663 --> 02:16:06.743
I'm a veteran of the Trojan War.

1560
02:16:08.063 --> 02:16:09.463
A veteran of the Trojan War.

1561
02:16:11.663 --> 02:16:13.603
And what's your name. veteran?

1562
02:16:18.503 --> 02:16:19.503
Sinon.

1563
02:16:22.368 --> 02:16:24.423
Does that name mean something to you?

1564
02:16:25.643 --> 02:16:26.643
No.

1565
02:16:27.763 --> 02:16:31.683
I use it to honor the bravest
young man I ever met.

1566
02:16:32.503 --> 02:16:33.503
Sinon?

1567
02:16:34.868 --> 02:16:36.303
I'm not just Shepard's boy.

1568
02:16:39.183 --> 02:16:40.339
I never remember that.

1569
02:16:40.363 --> 02:16:42.723
Yeah. yeah. he wanted
you to take his place.

1570
02:16:43.723 --> 02:16:44.723
Where does he find this?

1571
02:16:45.323 --> 02:16:46.503
Where he'll soon be.

1572
02:16:47.663 --> 02:16:48.663
And where is that?

1573
02:16:50.003 --> 02:16:51.003
Hades.

1574
02:16:54.163 --> 02:16:55.163
Enough!

1575
02:16:56.783 --> 02:16:58.343
The feast is done!

1576
02:17:04.403 --> 02:17:06.444
The scope… is not mine!

1577
02:17:15.043 --> 02:17:17.123
My queen would like to speak with you.

1578
02:17:17.603 --> 02:17:21.183
Stay till everyone's
left in the fires of the…

1579
02:18:10.823 --> 02:18:11.823
Hello. traveler.

1580
02:18:13.013 --> 02:18:14.013
My queen.

1581
02:18:14.572 --> 02:18:15.572
Melanthal?

1582
02:18:15.928 --> 02:18:17.893
Have Eurykleia washed the stranger's feet?

1583
02:18:18.523 --> 02:18:19.533
That's not necessary.

1584
02:18:19.798 --> 02:18:23.213
My husband insisted we
honor guests as family.

1585
02:18:24.178 --> 02:18:25.178
You know of a deceased?

1586
02:18:25.453 --> 02:18:26.453
My husband?

1587
02:18:26.653 --> 02:18:27.653
Of course.

1588
02:18:28.253 --> 02:18:29.253
Who are the souls?

1589
02:18:32.293 --> 02:18:33.913
And the songs probably seem silly.

1590
02:18:35.793 --> 02:18:36.793
They make me cry.

1591
02:18:37.993 --> 02:18:38.993
Why?

1592
02:18:39.943 --> 02:18:40.943
For what was lost.

1593
02:18:42.193 --> 02:18:43.193
The lives?

1594
02:18:43.953 --> 02:18:44.953
And the years.

1595
02:18:46.433 --> 02:18:47.433
Everything.

1596
02:18:55.262 --> 02:18:56.633
Did you know Eurykleia. said Troy?

1597
02:18:57.513 --> 02:18:58.513
I did.

1598
02:18:59.682 --> 02:19:03.473
Was there some detail of how
he dressed. something he wore?

1599
02:19:04.502 --> 02:19:05.810
He wore a strange pin.

1600
02:19:05.834 --> 02:19:07.193
Strange.

1601
02:19:08.793 --> 02:19:09.793
Beautiful.

1602
02:19:10.412 --> 02:19:11.412
But out of place.

1603
02:19:12.232 --> 02:19:13.232
Describe it.

1604
02:19:27.592 --> 02:19:28.663
I'll get more water.

1605
02:19:33.657 --> 02:19:35.863
It was a beautiful gold pin.

1606
02:19:37.437 --> 02:19:39.923
A figure of Athena encircled by vines.

1607
02:19:49.122 --> 02:19:50.122
Did he wear it often?

1608
02:19:52.042 --> 02:19:53.333
He never took it off.

1609
02:20:12.868 --> 02:20:16.043
How is it that you made it
home when Odysseus could not?

1610
02:20:17.463 --> 02:20:18.463
I'm not home.

1611
02:20:19.163 --> 02:20:20.163
Not yet.

1612
02:20:21.023 --> 02:20:22.023
Why not?

1613
02:20:22.672 --> 02:20:24.803
It's not always an easy
thing. a homecoming.

1614
02:20:25.922 --> 02:20:28.003
That's as true for Odysseus as for me.

1615
02:20:29.922 --> 02:20:36.982
The Odysseus I knew would have found or
fought his way back to me no matter what.

1616
02:20:38.152 --> 02:20:41.263
What if the Odysseus
you knew lost his way?

1617
02:20:50.602 --> 02:20:57.902
What if. one night. in a strange city. he
saw things that made him think the home

1618
02:20:58.152 --> 02:21:02.103
he knew couldn't
possibly be there anymore?

1619
02:21:06.452 --> 02:21:09.633
What if. when he left
the belly of the horse.

1620
02:21:13.938 --> 02:21:15.663
and opened the gates of Troy.

1621
02:21:21.533 --> 02:21:27.013
he saw ten years of rage
pour into that city in one night?

1622
02:22:30.593 --> 02:22:31.993
No!

1623
02:23:15.763 --> 02:23:16.120
No!

1624
02:23:16.144 --> 02:23:17.144
No!

1625
02:23:41.663 --> 02:23:45.543
We left them a gift.

1626
02:23:46.492 --> 02:23:51.543
An offering of peace that
they took into their home.

1627
02:24:01.982 --> 02:24:07.233
We violated all that's ever
sacred between people.

1628
02:24:09.983 --> 02:24:16.320
And turned a fight into a hunt.

1629
02:24:16.344 --> 02:24:17.344
No!

1630
02:24:17.643 --> 02:24:17.863
No!

1631
02:24:18.443 --> 02:24:19.443
No!

1632
02:24:27.793 --> 02:24:28.793
No!

1633
02:24:32.293 --> 02:24:40.293
To burn the walls of Troy was to burn
the world entire. including his home.

1634
02:24:47.342 --> 02:24:51.183
What if he knew that very night.

1635
02:24:54.703 --> 02:24:58.843
as he walked through
fires of anarchy and pain.

1636
02:25:47.713 --> 02:25:51.313
and in the days of sweaty
celebrations to follow.

1637
02:25:57.553 --> 02:26:01.033
what if he knew exactly what he'd done?

1638
02:26:19.733 --> 02:26:21.303
What all of you had done?

1639
02:26:21.828 --> 02:26:23.063
One man's idea.

1640
02:26:25.032 --> 02:26:26.083
One man's trick.

1641
02:26:28.177 --> 02:26:30.463
To break Zeus' law forever.

1642
02:26:32.102 --> 02:26:34.963
We lived in a world of palaces and trade.

1643
02:26:37.172 --> 02:26:42.183
A language blind to its
beauty. until we broke it.

1644
02:26:44.983 --> 02:26:46.883
You were the people from the sea?

1645
02:26:49.782 --> 02:26:50.782
Yes. my queen.

1646
02:26:52.542 --> 02:26:55.543
The breaking of Zeus' law
is spreading like plague.

1647
02:26:56.098 --> 02:26:57.923
Our age of bronze is collapsing.

1648
02:26:58.442 --> 02:27:01.163
And maybe he couldn't bear to
see the ruins of what he'd done.

1649
02:27:02.408 --> 02:27:03.408
Anywhere.

1650
02:27:03.783 --> 02:27:05.363
Least of all. his home.

1651
02:27:15.713 --> 02:27:16.753
Odysseus is alive.

1652
02:27:19.242 --> 02:27:20.993
And he'll be here when you need him most.

1653
02:27:26.062 --> 02:27:28.933
I've been living in his ruins long enough.

1654
02:27:33.993 --> 02:27:35.333
Bring the suitors at dawn.

1655
02:27:35.748 --> 02:27:37.053
Remove the arms from the hall.

1656
02:27:37.633 --> 02:27:41.790
In a few hours. one suitor will be
happy. and the rest. angry. vengeful men.

1657
02:27:41.814 --> 02:27:46.674
Ron draws a man on so he'll have no weapons
at the trial. and the doors will be locked.

1658
02:27:47.168 --> 02:27:49.093
I'll marry whoever completes my challenge.

1659
02:27:55.933 --> 02:27:57.563
How will we take on the suitors?

1660
02:27:58.643 --> 02:27:59.643
Not we.

1661
02:28:00.538 --> 02:28:02.123
Their blood belongs on my hands.

1662
02:28:03.098 --> 02:28:04.183
Or you'd face exile.

1663
02:28:05.563 --> 02:28:06.563
Won't you?

1664
02:28:07.642 --> 02:28:09.402
Just make sure they
can't get those weapons.

1665
02:28:10.058 --> 02:28:11.058
I'll see to it.

1666
02:28:11.952 --> 02:28:13.723
Even unarmed. there are so many of them.

1667
02:28:14.783 --> 02:28:15.903
And you won't have a weapon.

1668
02:28:17.842 --> 02:28:18.842
Well. I'll have a weapon.

1669
02:28:20.872 --> 02:28:22.043
Your mother's seen to that.

1670
02:28:24.872 --> 02:28:26.523
Gather the servants you trust.

1671
02:28:26.788 --> 02:28:28.943
Lock the arms in the upper storage room.

1672
02:29:21.563 --> 02:29:23.863
She seems interested in the outcome.

1673
02:29:24.443 --> 02:29:25.443
But what's the trial?

1674
02:29:49.583 --> 02:29:53.868
For years. while my
husband's been gone. you've

1675
02:29:53.892 --> 02:29:58.004
commandeered this
palace for your feasting.

1676
02:29:58.523 --> 02:30:01.403
Your excuse was you wanted
to win my hand in marriage.

1677
02:30:06.983 --> 02:30:14.960
As I listen to you party. and fight.
corrupt my servants. and disrespect my

1678
02:30:14.984 --> 02:30:16.988
home. I've wanted nothing more than for.

1679
02:30:17.012 --> 02:30:20.484
Odysseus to return and
see all this for himself.

1680
02:30:26.283 --> 02:30:31.843
But last night. I realized
he's not here now.

1681
02:30:34.423 --> 02:30:36.323
He never will be.

1682
02:30:38.783 --> 02:30:44.683
So. I stand ready to marry
anyone here who can string this

1683
02:30:44.707 --> 02:30:48.503
hunting bow and shoot an
arrow through those twelve axes.

1684
02:30:50.543 --> 02:30:52.023
Step up.

1685
02:30:53.303 --> 02:30:55.343
And show me who you are.

1686
02:30:56.943 --> 02:30:57.943
Eumaeus.

1687
02:31:09.233 --> 02:31:10.433
Who's first?

1688
02:31:11.253 --> 02:31:12.253
Give me the bow.

1689
02:31:32.093 --> 02:31:33.690
It can't be done.

1690
02:31:33.714 --> 02:31:34.714
Hey. you.

1691
02:31:35.693 --> 02:31:37.393
It's a boy I saw Odysseus do with ease.

1692
02:31:38.033 --> 02:31:39.033
Then you do it.

1693
02:31:39.848 --> 02:31:40.848
I'll wait my turn.

1694
02:31:42.153 --> 02:31:44.113
Why don't we warm the bow and oil it?

1695
02:31:45.822 --> 02:31:47.553
This bow hasn't been strong in years.

1696
02:32:20.838 --> 02:32:21.838
Your turn.

1697
02:32:22.588 --> 02:32:23.588
There's no need.

1698
02:32:26.918 --> 02:32:28.078
The queen has made her point.

1699
02:32:28.993 --> 02:32:30.163
We can't replace Odysseus.

1700
02:32:30.708 --> 02:32:32.068
Some of us have always known that.

1701
02:32:32.328 --> 02:32:36.083
Some of us would have followed
that great man. Detroit. if he'd let us.

1702
02:32:39.192 --> 02:32:40.383
But he never came back.

1703
02:32:42.658 --> 02:32:44.343
So choose the best of us here.

1704
02:32:46.062 --> 02:32:47.903
All of us who failed your test.

1705
02:32:48.302 --> 02:32:51.103
I haven't.

1706
02:32:54.563 --> 02:32:56.503
Somebody get these beggars out of here.

1707
02:32:57.463 --> 02:33:00.023
The doors are locked
until the trial's over.

1708
02:33:00.443 --> 02:33:01.923
The trial is over.

1709
02:33:02.923 --> 02:33:03.943
I want to try.

1710
02:33:07.603 --> 02:33:09.263
He has a right to try.

1711
02:33:10.543 --> 02:33:12.643
If he won't. he may as well.

1712
02:33:13.263 --> 02:33:15.183
You're making a mockery
of your mother's wishes.

1713
02:33:15.403 --> 02:33:17.783
My mother's wishes
are for you all to burn.

1714
02:33:28.683 --> 02:33:31.383
He's an old archer.

1715
02:33:36.363 --> 02:33:38.563
Look at the expert at work.

1716
02:33:41.303 --> 02:33:43.623
Hold that.

1717
02:33:43.743 --> 02:33:44.743
Forget it.

1718
02:33:56.773 --> 02:33:58.573
Friend. that's enough.

1719
02:34:43.403 --> 02:34:44.403
You're a dis.

1720
02:34:51.583 --> 02:34:53.673
Surely your place is down there.

1721
02:35:07.213 --> 02:35:08.213
Is it him?

1722
02:35:09.773 --> 02:35:10.773
It's him!

1723
02:35:35.263 --> 02:35:36.963
Where are the weapons?

1724
02:35:37.723 --> 02:35:38.723
They're up a storm.

1725
02:35:38.883 --> 02:35:39.883
Get them!

1726
02:35:45.403 --> 02:35:47.103
They're gonna kill us all!

1727
02:35:51.983 --> 02:35:58.043
I told you.

1728
02:35:58.443 --> 02:35:59.763
Too loud. cowherd.

1729
02:37:17.443 --> 02:37:19.483
Get the doors!

1730
02:38:12.433 --> 02:38:20.433
Get the doors!

1731
02:38:21.013 --> 02:38:22.013
Get the doors!

1732
02:39:00.643 --> 02:39:01.643
Spear!

1733
02:40:26.513 --> 02:40:28.373
Thought you could kill us all.

1734
02:40:29.553 --> 02:40:30.773
As long as I kill you.

1735
02:40:32.273 --> 02:40:33.273
Finish this.

1736
02:40:36.313 --> 02:40:37.313
Dad!

1737
02:40:55.373 --> 02:41:00.833
I'll kill you!

1738
02:41:01.213 --> 02:41:09.163
When you get to Hades…

1739
02:41:10.743 --> 02:41:14.963
Tell my men I will head
west and honor them.

1740
02:41:20.843 --> 02:41:26.703
And tell Cenon… I gave
you back your shame.

1741
02:41:45.783 --> 02:41:46.923
What happened?

1742
02:41:48.983 --> 02:41:49.983
Did he beat them?

1743
02:41:51.508 --> 02:41:52.508
Is he dead?

1744
02:41:54.522 --> 02:41:56.943
We broke the fragile bonds between men.

1745
02:42:05.398 --> 02:42:08.103
And for centuries of darkness to follow

1746
02:42:09.028 --> 02:42:12.463
the stories of Troy… will only be sung.

1747
02:43:32.443 --> 02:43:33.923
What is this. Willa?

1748
02:43:35.383 --> 02:43:38.853
What is this?

1749
02:43:39.698 --> 02:43:42.113
Willa. you get back.

1750
02:43:43.993 --> 02:43:44.993
At last.

1751
02:43:45.913 --> 02:43:46.913
The end.

1752
02:43:48.587 --> 02:43:50.093
To see my beloved Ithaca.

1753
02:43:51.263 --> 02:43:52.413
One last time.

1754
02:43:54.193 --> 02:43:54.733
No.

1755
02:43:55.173 --> 02:43:56.173
No. no. you can't.

1756
02:43:56.253 --> 02:43:56.693
You can't.

1757
02:43:56.813 --> 02:43:57.173
You can't.

1758
02:43:57.213 --> 02:43:57.413
Not now.

1759
02:43:57.633 --> 02:43:58.193
Not now. please.

1760
02:43:58.308 --> 02:43:59.308
Every single one of us.

1761
02:44:01.672 --> 02:44:02.793
You can't die.

1762
02:44:04.118 --> 02:44:05.233
Not death.

1763
02:44:07.933 --> 02:44:08.933
Exile.

1764
02:44:17.263 --> 02:44:18.383
Telemachus will be king.

1765
02:44:22.783 --> 02:44:24.303
We'll head into the unknown west.

1766
02:44:30.103 --> 02:44:36.483
Take your fastest ship… and greatest
crew… and head for the horizon.

1767
02:44:37.943 --> 02:44:39.623
Chasing the escaping sun.

1768
02:44:42.203 --> 02:44:44.103
Why will the stories only be sung?

1769
02:44:47.143 --> 02:44:50.683
Because songs will be all they have to
remember those of us who could write.

1770
02:44:55.903 --> 02:44:57.783
Civilization will rise again.

1771
02:45:03.903 --> 02:45:06.823
A new dawn will break
over the darkened world.

1772
02:45:10.449 --> 02:45:13.009
And our mistakes will
once again be forgotten.
